title - A Crash Course in Assistive Technology
p - Work and other activities can be greatly affected when an individual has a disability. Many people adapt by using assistive technology. Assistive technology is any physical or digital product, device, or system that helps people with disabilities increase their independence or functional abilities. These tools improve the academic and professional experiences of students, staff, and faculty, allowing them to work without barriers.
p - In this article, we'll explore several types of assistive technology for digital content and web use. The information below is a starting point, not an exhaustive list, as the effectiveness of these tools varies greatly depending on the individual.
h2 - Vision
h3 - Magnification
p - Screen magnification technology enlarges on-screen content, making it easier to see for users with visual impairments. This technology functions like a digital magnifying glass, following the cursor and zooming in on the desired area.
h3 - Color Overlay
p - Color-adjusting/screen overlay assistive technology is a software tool that modifies a device's screen colors and contrast to improve visibility and readability for individuals with visual impairments.
h3 - Text-to-Speech (TTS)
p - Text-to-speech technology, or read-aloud technology, converts written text into spoken words, aiding users in reading comprehension and writing improvement.
h3 - Screen Readers
p - Screen readers are essential software for individuals with disabilities affecting vision. They use a voice synthesizer to convert all meaningful on-screen content like text, images, links, and buttons into speech. This technology provides users with an audio version of the digital world, allowing them to navigate websites, read documents, and access other digital resources with auditory cues.
h2 - Hearing
h3 - Closed Captions (CC) and Transcripts
p - Closed captions are synchronized text that appears on screen with the corresponding audio. Not only do they display spoken words, but they also include non-speech sounds and other auditory information. Building on this concept, transcriptions are text versions of a complete video or live event. Transcripts provide a full account of the video content. In addition to detailing the audio, they provide visual context, actions, and expressions.
h3 - Assistive Listening Devices (ALD)
p - Assistive listening devices improve a person's ability to hear by amplifying the sounds they want to hear while reducing background noise. They work by transmitting sound directly to a user's ear through various methods, including the use of radio signals, a thin wire to send a signal, and microphones that boost a speaker's voice. Some devices can also connect wirelessly to a smartphone or other device using Bluetooth technology.
h3 - Alerting Devices
p - Alerting devices are designed to notify people of sounds in their environment, such as a smoke alarm, a doorbell, or a ringing phone, using visual or vibrating signals. Many personal devices, such as cell phones and smartwatches, also have built-in alerting features.
h3 - Communication Technology
p - Telecommunication Relay Services (TRS) provide a bridge for individuals with hearing disabilities to make and receive phone calls. These services use either a live interpreter or automated speech-to-text conversion to relay conversations, allowing users to communicate via video or text. Some services use a sign language interpreter to relay messages via a videophone, while others use an app to display a real-time transcript of the conversation.
h2 - Speech Communication
h3 - Speech Generation
p - Speech-generating Devices (SGD) are electronic "talking devices" that help users with speech disabilities communicate. These devices generate synthesized or recorded words and phrases when a user selects a button or icon. SGDs are highly adaptable and can be operated in various ways, including touchscreens, eye tracking, or head pointers, allowing them to meet a wide range of user needs.
h3 - Electronic Fluency
p - Electronic Fluency Devices are tools designed for individuals who stutter or have other fluency challenges. They work by providing auditory feedback that helps a person change how they hear their own voice, which can improve fluency. This technology is often delivered through a variety of methods, such as playing the user’s voice back with a slight delay or changing its pitch in real time.
h3 - Voice Amplification
p - Voice Amplification Devices help users who have difficulty projecting their voice loudly. These devices consist of a microphone and a speaker, making the user's voice more audible and clearer, which can help reduce speech anxiety. Voice amplifiers are available as small, wearable devices, and many personal devices, such as smartphones, now have built-in amplification features for phone calls.
h2 - Learning & Cognition
h3 - Information Organization
p - Organizational tools assist with processing and structuring information. Technologies such as mind-mapping software provide a visual way to organize complex information into clear, manageable segments. Similarly, note-taking applications offer a variety of features to help individuals capture and organize information in an accessible format.
h3 - Writing and Math Support
p - These tools help individuals who experience challenges with academic tasks. Writing support software, for example, makes the physical act of writing more manageable by providing features like voice-to-text, grammar and spell correction, and text prediction. Math accessibility software makes equations easier to use by offering features such as text-to-speech for reading equations aloud, interactive interfaces, and step-by-step guidance.
h3 - Memory and Task Management
p - Memory and productivity aids help individuals with cognitive challenges and memory issues with essential everyday tasks. Memory assistance technology, for example, aids with retaining and recalling information, which can reduce anxiety related to forgetfulness. Similarly, productivity and time-tracking apps use reminders, scheduling tools, and visual aids to help users prioritize and manage their tasks effectively.
h2 - Mobility
h3 - Alternative Input Devices
p - Alternative input devices allow individuals with mobility disabilities to interact with digital devices using non-traditional methods. By replacing the standard keyboard and mouse, these tools provide users with greater freedom and independence. Examples include eye-tracking systems, switch devices, and adaptive keyboards.
h3 - Voice Recognition
p - Voice recognition technology, also known as dictation, empowers individuals by converting spoken words into text and commands. This assistive tool facilitates hands-free interaction with devices, allowing users to not only write emails or create documents but also to navigate digital content and the web by voice. The software's accuracy often improves over time as it recognizes a person's unique speech patterns.
h2 - Conclusion
p - In an increasingly digital world, assistive technology serves as a vital bridge, removing the barriers that can prevent full participation. Tools for adapting digital and web content are constantly evolving, providing innovative solutions for a wide range of challenges. The continued development and adoption of these technologies are key to ensuring that everyone has the opportunity to succeed and thrive in the digital world.


