title - ARIA
h2 - Understand
p - Learn more about the content format and common accessibility issues before working with ARIA.
p - Accessible Rich Internet Applications (ARIA) is a set of roles and attributes designed to enhance web accessibility for individuals who use assistive technologies (AT). ARIA enables developers to add semantic meaning and interactivity to HTML when native mechanisms do not exist. ARIA roles, states, and properties provide additional semantic information to assistive technologies. Think of ARIA as the "voice" that communicates the purpose and behavior of web elements to screen readers and other AT.
p - Never use ARIA to hide accessibility problems or bad code. Use ARIA to enhance and add additional information. Use ARIA to cloak, or hide original semantics, like with a link in a menu or navigation as a menu item using a role or you could hide a visible label with an expanded aria-label. Be careful and mindful about using these methods because the original semantic information is still available. Use ARIA to add context and support, or enhance existing semantics, like with the state of a button as pressed or not using aria-pressed.
h3 - Frequently Asked Questions
h4 - When should ARIA be used?
p - Use ARIA only when necessary to support semantic and native HTML; ARIA is a supplement, not a replacement. Many native HTML elements are inherently accessible and preferred because they are already supported by various input types and assistive technologies. If you are unsure of what ARIA to use, it is better to use no ARIA rather than mislead with incorrect ARIA.
p - According to WebAim's survey of over one million home pages, “The more ARIA attributes that were present, the more detected accessibility errors could be expected.”
h4 - What are the benefits of ARIA
h4 - What are the limitations of ARIA?
p - Assigning a role is a commitment that element functions as described. Breaking this promise (e.g., assigning the role of button to a static image) misleads users and creates digital accessibility barriers rather than improving accessibility. Keeping the promise provided in a role maintains a consistent and accessible digital experience.
h2 - Create
p - Learn more about ARIA creation principles. Applying the Aspects will address the most common digital accessibility issues and make the content more accessible and user-friendly. Focus on the Best Practices after all the Aspects have been applied. They are “nice-to-haves” in accessibility but not as urgent.
h3 - Apply the Aspects
h4 - Usability
p - ARIA enhances usability by improving the user experience for those who rely on assistive technologies.
h4 - Real Text
p - ARIA is not a replacement for real text, but it is used to provide accessible names and descriptions for elements that may not have them.
h4 - Structure
p - ARIA is essential for defining the structure and purpose of a website when semantic HTML is not used or is insufficient.
h4 - Sensory Characteristics
p - ARIA helps convey sensory characteristics that are not visually or audibly obvious.
h4 - Visual Content
p - ARIA is not used to describe visual content directly, but rather to provide a textual alternative to it.
h3 - Best Practices
h4 - Accordions
p - Accordions are commonly used to reduce the need to scroll when presenting multiple sections of content on a single page. Add aria-expanded to indicate whether the section is open or closed. Add aria-controls to connect the content panel to the header.
h4 - Carousels
p - A carousel presents a set of items, referred to as slides, by sequentially displaying a subset of one or more slides. Typically, one slide is displayed at a time. Then user controls or automated rotations moves to the next or previous slide, hiding the current slide. Add aria-live to announce changes in the content. Use aria-label to describe each slide. Use aria-roledescription to provide a description of the functionality.
h2 - Evaluate
p - Walk through a quick accessibility check for content that has already been created to evaluate its accessibility. For an in-depth evaluation download the content checklist to get a quantitative score.
h3 - Quick Accessibility Check
p - Is ARIA used only when necessary and where native HTML is insufficient?
p - Are correct ARIA landmarks used to complement HTML structure?
p - Is ARIA used to assist with communicating dynamic content?
p - Is ARIA use reviewed for correct use?
h2 - Decide
p - Learn more about what to do with evaluation data and how to pick which content is most accessible.
h3 - Remediation
p - After evaluating your content, you may find several accessibility issues. Prioritize remediating content that has the greatest impact on the user.
p - Once you've decided on the most critical accessibility issues to address, it's time to implement changes. This may involve:
p - Semantic Structure: Use ARIA roles to define the purpose of a page's regions.
p - Dynamic State: Use ARIA states and properties to tell screen readers about the status of interactive elements that change.
p - Labels: Use area labels to provide a clear name for elements that don't have visible text.
p - For more help request accessibility assistance for your content or schedule a training with a specialist, in person or online. These trainings can be as quick as 15mins or as long as an hour. They will teach you more about creating accessible content and answer additional questions you may have.
