title - Audio-Only
h2 - Understand
p - Learn more about the content format and common accessibility issues before working with audio-only content.
p - Audio can cover a wide range of content, but this page will focus solely on pre-recorded audio-only content. Audio (such as podcasts, audiobooks, voice notes, instructional recordings, etc.) should be usable and understandable by people who are deaf or hard of hearing, as well as those with cognitive, auditory processing, or language barriers. The goal is for everyone, regardless of hearing ability or comprehension needs, to have access to the information conveyed through audio content.
p - Audio content falls short when it lacks transcripts, has poor audio quality, unclear speech, lacks contextual information, and the platform is inaccessible. Not everyone processes spoken language equally so backup formats help bridge the gap and give an equal experience to all users.
h3 - Frequently Asked Questions
h4 - When are audio files most useful?
p - Appropriate use cases include storytelling and narrative information, short informational briefings, and supplemental or accessible alternative for other content.
h4 - What are the benefits of audio files?
p - The benefits of using this format include convenience and flexiblity for consuming content in many ways and locations. Cost-effective and less resource intensive than producing video content.
h4 - What are the limitations on audio files?
p - Some limitations include exclusion of some audiences, especially hard of hearing. Contextual understanding of concepts or nuanced information.
h3 - Recommended Software
p - Note: Since the user doesn't need to open the audio file with the same software it was created with, the actual software used for creation isn't as important as the media player. If the audio content follows good creation practices it should be accessible to the user.
h4 - Audacity
p - Audacity is an easy-to-use, multi-track audio editor and recorder for Windows, macOS, GNU/Linux and other operating systems. Audacity is free, open source software.
h4 - GarageBand
p - GarageBand is a fully equipped music creation studio right inside your Mac… With an intuitive, modern design, it’s easy to learn, play, record, create, and share your hits worldwide.
h2 - Create
p - Learn more about audio-only creation principles. Applying the Aspects will address the most common accessibility issues and make the content more accessible and user-friendly. Focus on the Best Practices after all the Aspects have been applied. They are “nice-to-haves” in digital accessibility but not as urgent.
h3 - Apply the Aspects
h4 - Usability
p - Choose a media player that can be accessed using various input types (i.e. keyboard navigation). There is a list of recommended media players in the Understand section of this page.
p - The content should be presented with accessibility in mind. If the speaker has any visuals, they should describe them to the audience. It is helpful to write a script beforehand so that nothing is left out.
h4 - Real Text
h4 - Structure
p - Use the transcript to create the audio content when possible (an exception being a conversational podcast). This helps keep the content organized and easy to understand.
p - Chapter markers can be added to section out the audio and aid with understanding. If sections are added, include them in the transcript as well.
p - Any links in the transcript should be read in the audio. This ensures that those who are unable to read the transcript will still get the same information.
h4 - Sensory Characteristics
p - Media player controls should have proper contrast in all states (started, paused, etc.) The controls should still be visible if the page is magnified or the device orientation has changed.
p - If the audio auto-plays, the user should be able to pause it within 5 seconds.
h4 - Visual Content
p - The media player controls should be sufficiently large and easy to click. They should also have proper labels so the computer can read them out if necessary. It is possible to test this using a screen reader or by looking at the code (for websites).
h3 - Best Practices
h4 - Content
p - The language should be clear and concise. All jargon should be defined and explained, this includes any technical terms and acronyms. The speaker should be as clear as possible, avoiding filler words and sounds as much as possible.
h4 - Audio Quality
p - The audio must be clear and easy to understand, without static or distortion. The volume and speech rate will be consistent and balanced. The overlap of speakers should be minimized as much as possible. The audio should be optimized for mono playback.
h4 - Technical
p - The downloadable audio file should have clear metadata.
h2 - Evaluate
p - Walk through a quick accessibility check for content that is already been created to evaluate its accessibility. For an in-depth evaluation download the content checklist to get a quantitative score.
h3 - Quick Accessibility Check
p - Review the Transcript - Spot check the audio transcript for completeness and accessibility. The transcript should be a complete clean verbatim version of the audio.
p - Ensure High Quality Audio - Avoid static, quality, background noise, and unclear speech as much as possible. If an audio track quality is bad enough, consider rerecording it or finding another alternative.
p - Check Player Controls - Use the Tab key to move through the player controls. Use the Enter or Spacebar to try activating them. Ensure they can all be controlled using just keyboard keys.
h2 - Decide
p - Learn more about what to do with evaluation data and how to pick which content is most accessible.
h3 - What to Choose
p - It can be difficult to encounter fully accessible audio files. Ideally, find files with a transcript/text alternative so that users will still be able to receive the content in another format. When deciding on what content to provide, try to ensure that it is appropriately accessible. Here is a list of some things to focus on when providing accessible content:
p - Accessible file formats, such as MP3 and WAV
p - Audio with companion transcripts/descriptions
p - Closed Captions
p - For more help, request accessibility assistance for your content or schedule a training with a specialist, in person or online. These trainings can be as quick as 15mins or as long as an hour. They will teach you more about creating accessible content and answer additional questions you may have.
