title - Captioning
p - An important element of video accessibility is captioning. If you are creating content, make sure you plan time to add captions that accurately reflect your content. If you are using someone else's content, take a moment to check if there are quality captions. The accessibility goal of captioning is that someone who only listens to the audio track and someone who only reads the captions are engaging in the same experience.
p - Captions are not the same as subtitles. Subtitles provide a transcription of the dialogue in a video in either the same or different language as the audio. Captions are a direct clean verbatim transcription of the entire audio track in the audio language. The goal is not to provide clarity but to provide an equivalent experience in text form. Closed captions may be turned on or off by the user and are available to assistive technology. Open captions are burned into the video. We recommend using closed captions whenever possible.
h2 - Quality Caption Components
p - These five components should be used to check if previously captioned content needs different or more accurate captions. If the video captions satisfy all five questions, we determine it is good enough, unless user feedback says otherwise.
p - Have the captions been edited for accuracy? - Captions should be a minimum of 98% accurate to the clean verbatim spoken content. Unedited auto-generated captions do not meet internal accessibility requirements.
p - Are different speakers identified? - If the speaker name is not important (e.g., narrator, voiceover, single speaker), speaker identification can be omitted. If there are only two speakers, simple identification of a speaker change (>>, --, etc.) qualifies. Other speakers, on or off screen, should be identified by title and/or last name. If last name is unknown, first name may be used in lieu of last. If no name is known, another appropriate identifier may be used.
p - Are captions timed and broken up correctly? - Captions should be timed to match the content. Captions should remain on screen with adequate time for the user to read. Captions should be in consistent lines and rows.
p - Are important sounds identified? - Sounds (on and off screen) relevant or responsive to spoken content should be in captions, identified in brackets. Long silences should be noted as well. Important tone or emotional speaking modifiers should be identified.
p - Are punctuation and capitalization included to accurately portray meaning and clarity? - Correct punctuation and capitalization can help provide structure and clarity to captions. Intentional punctuation can help portray meaning; this is especially important with pauses, interruptions, or fade outs.
h2 - General Guidelines
p - Creating high-quality captions involves more than just a verbatim transcription of audio content. At a high-level, captions have three different pieces that we want to be aware of: formatting (presentation) of content, speech, and non-speech information.
h3 - Formatting
p - We want our captions to be consistently formatted so they are predictable. This means include only one sentence per caption box, with no more than 2 lines. Each line should be no longer than 35 characters, for a maximum of 70 characters per box. If two lines are used in one box, both lines should be split as evenly as possible where a sentence normally pauses (clauses, phrases, etc.). As a general rule, caption boxes should be on the screen for a minimum of 1 second, and a maximum of 6-7 seconds.
p - Each speaker should be identified using their last name in all capital letters, followed by a colon, placed before their captioned speech. Speakers should be identified every time the speaker changes.
h3 - Speech
p - When making captions, speech information takes priority. Caption content as clean verbatim, which means that minor grammatical errors may be removed if it will substantially improve the experience and excess filles can be omitted. Any slang, jargon, or special dialects should be captioned as they are. Don't censor or modify swearing or explicit language unless it is censored in the audio track.
p - If a speaker says something that can't be easily identified, write [inaudible] or [indistinct] (enclosed in square brackets) to take place of the speech in question.
h3 - Non-speech Information
p - For content that isn't speech (such as a sound, silence, or music that isn't integral to the understanding of the content), use the following hierarchy to determine whether it should be included in the captions:
p - Essential: Crucial to understanding meaning of development; these should always be added.
p - Accessory: Helpful but not essential (tone, mood, periphery sounds); these can be added when time and space permit.
p - Minimal: Incidental and information-limited; not needed, these should be added only if no other information takes priority.
p - Continuous sounds (silence, sounds, or background music that lasts more than 10 seconds) should be on the screen for a minimum of 5 seconds, and a maximum of 10 seconds. If the sound is still playing 30 seconds after, include another indicator that the sound is still playing. Identify the source of the sound if not visually apparent.
