title - Captioning Style Guide
h2 - Formatting
h3 - Division
p - Captions are broken into boxes (what appears on screen at one time), and boxes are broken into lines. There should be one sentence per box with no more than 70 total characters (35 characters per line) in 1–2 lines, split as evenly as possible. Avoid wildly differing line lengths in a box.
p - !! Short, related sentences containing one or two words by a single speaker can be in a single box, on different lines.
h3 - Duration
p - Caption boxes should appear on screen for the length of the time that matches the audio for the contents. Caption boxes should also remain on screen long enough for users to read the contents.
p - !! Music and continuing sounds or silence may be on screen for up to 10 seconds.
h3 - Speaker Identification
p - Each speaker should be identified using a unique identifier in all capital letters followed by a colon. Speakers should be identified every time the speaker changes. Default identification is the speaker’s last name.
h3 - Other On-screen Elements
p - When possible, captions should not interfere with or cover important on-screen elements, such as open captions, translations, or visuals. This may mean adjusting line lengths, duration, or having one line per box.
h2 - Speech Information
h3 - Verbatim
p - Captions should represent the entirety of the audio track at a minimum of 98% verbatim accuracy. Minor grammatical errors, deletions, repeats, and fillers may be corrected if it will substantially improve the user experience.
p - !! Do not modify or censor swearing or other explicit language unless censored in the audio track.
p - !! If there are questions about how to caption, caption verbatim.
h3 - Unintelligible or Unclear Speech
p - If a speaker says something entirely inaudible or otherwise unintelligible, write inaudible (too quiet) or indistinct (not understandable) enclosed in square brackets to take place of the speech in question.
h3 - Foreign Language
p - Captions should include audio transcription of the entire audio track in the language of the audio track.
p - !! If there is no expectation the user should be able to understand the foreign language, a descriptor may be used.
h2 - Punctuation
h3 - General
p - Follow our internal style guide and Chicago style guide whenever possible, unless it will impede clarity. It is acceptable to start sentences with conjunctions to break up run on sentences.
p - !! Avoid using colons outside of scripture references, time, and speaker identification.
p - !! Avoid semi-colons except when used as a super-comma in a list.
h3 - Breaks in Speech
p - Use a suspension (...) to indicate speech that trails off or if a speaker starts a new train of thought.
p - Use a double hyphen (--) for jarring breaks, speaker corrections, or external interruptions.
p - !! If there is a silence in the middle of a sentence, and the silence is more than 10 seconds, add a descriptor for the silence.
h3 - Dashes and Hyphens
p - Use a single hyphen for an en dash. Use two consecutive hyphens for an em dash.
h2 - Style
h3 - Numbers
p - All single-digit numbers, including zero, should be spelled out. All other numbers should be expressed with numerals. Use commas in numbers with four or more digits.
p - !! Always use numerals with an en dash (no spaces) for a range.
h3 - Mathematics
p - Always use numerals for math equations, decimals, descriptions, or formulas, except for zero.
h3 - Symbols
p - Write out names for symbols and variables, except for percentages not beginning a sentence.
h3 - Dates and Times
p - Follow the formatting of the speaker. Always use numerals in dates and times.
p - If the day comes before the month, do not include a comma. If the month comes before the day, add a comma before the year. Never include an ordinal form (‑th, ‑rd, ‑st, etc.), unless the day is referenced without a month or year.
h3 - Special Topics
p - Be consistent throughout video for specialized subjects and topics, such as coding, chemistry, etc.
h3 - Computers
p - If referencing a keyboard key, use a capital letter, numeral, or symbol.
p - If referencing key combinations, use a +, no spaces, and spell out symbols.
p - If referencing menu selections, separate selections with comma. Match capitalization and spelling for on screen and menu elements.
p - !! Type URLs and web addresses as normal, including punctuation.
h3 - Measurements
p - Do not abbreviate units of measurement (for example centimeters, newtons, feet, etc.).
h3 - Money
p - If the speaker directly references money (dollars, bucks, etc.), use the dollar symbol ($) with numerals. Write out verbatim if it is a single-digit number. Use the dollar symbol with a decimal number for all references to cents.
p - !! If the speaker does not specifically reference money (by saying dollars, bucks, etc.), omit the reference ($) in the captions.
h3 - Scripture References
p - Write all scripture references as if they were parenthetical citations using a colon to separate chapter and verse (e.g., 1 Nephi 3:7).
h3 - Quotes
p - Enclose all quoted text in quotation marks no matter who the quote is from. If speech is given as if it is an exact quote, enclose it in quotation marks.
p - !! If a speaker uses a formal lead-in or close to a quote (start quote, end quote, etc.), designate with only quotation marks, not verbatim text.
p - !! Reading on screen text or from a screen does not make speech a quote.
h3 - Words and Letters
p - Capitalize all single letters used in reference on their own; pluralize letters using ‘s.
p - Words used for the word should be enclosed in quotation marks to indicate that the word itself is used not its meaning.
p - When spelling, separate capital letters with dashes and no spaces.
h3 - Music
p - In captioning, music is defined as anything sung or played in a rhythmic and melodic manner. Identify music with a double music note (♪♪) to start and end. Start and end music and lyrics the same way; start and end each caption box in the middle with a single music note (♪).
p - Note: To type a musical note, you can hold down Alt and type 13 on your numpad.
p - !! Lyrics that are spoken should be styled as quoted text.
h2 - Non-Speech Sounds
h3 - General
p - Non-speech information relevant to the audience should be indicated in all lowercase text enclosed in square brackets. Non-speech information is relevant if it provides information to the audience, interrupts the speaker, or if a speaker references the sound.
p - All relevant non-speech information (sounds) should occupy a box by itself unless the speaker made the sound.
h3 - Hierarchy of Relevancy
p - If there is a conflict between the non-speech information, use the following hierarchy to determine what information to include:
p - Essential - Crucial to understanding meaning or development. Always include this information.
p - Accessory - Helpful, but not essential. Include when possible.
p - Minimal - Incidental and information-limited. Include only when time and space allow.
h3 - Source
p - Identify the source of a sound if it is not clearly seen on screen.
p - !! The source does not need to be repeated if the sound continues.
h3 - Verb Tense
p - Sounds made by the speaker, or external abrupt sounds, should use the third person present tense (‑s). Sustained sounds external to the speaker should use the present participle form (‑ing).
h3 - Tone Modification
p - A speaker with a notable accent should be described as having such, particularly if it plays a role in their grammar or ease of understanding.
p - !! Retain dialect and colloquial words and phrases used by speakers with accents.
p - If a speaker modifies tone in a significant way, indicate it with a descriptor. Speech modification descriptors should be adverbs or participles.
