title - Cascading Style Sheets (CSS)
h2 - Understand
p - Learn more about the content format and common accessibility issues before working with CSS.
p - CSS (Cascading Style Sheets) is a stylesheet language used to control the presentation of web content, including layout, colors, fonts, and spacing, to create visually appealing and functional designs. In the context of digital accessibility, CSS helps make content easier to see, navigate, and use for everyone, including people with disabilities. Proper use of CSS can enhance accessibility by supporting responsive design, enabling customization for user preferences, and ensuring visual cues like focus indicators and sufficient contrast. However, CSS must be implemented carefully, as misuse (e.g., relying on fixed layouts or using color alone to convey information) can create barriers for assistive technologies and diverse user needs.
p - The content and functionality of a webpage should be fully understandable and usable even if CSS is disabled or not loading. This principle ensures that users relying on screen readers, text-only browsers, or those with limited internet access can still access all critical information.
p - CSS provides a mechanism for adding styles such as fonts, colors, spacing to web content. CSS tells technology how to display the information.
h3 - Frequently Asked Questions
h4 - When should CSS be used?
p - To improve the appearance of webpages and help users understand content better.
h4 - What are the benefits of CSS?
p - CSS is ideal for organizing the visual presentation of content and creating responsive designs.
h4 - What are the drawbacks of CSS?
p - CSS can override defaults which may cause accessibility issues (i.e. other styling makes the keyboard focus invisible).
h2 - Create
p - Learn more about creating accessible audio files. The Aspects address the most common accessibility issues. Following these principles will help make more accessible and user-friendly content. Best practices are “nice-to-haves” in accessibility; focus on these after applying the aspects.
h3 - Apply the Aspects
h4 - Usability
p - Relative Units: Allow users to adjust settings like font size, line height, and color schemes to meet their individual needs. Use relative units like em, rem, and percentages (%) for fonts, text containers, column widths, padding, and margins.
h4 - Real Text
p - CSS can help text adapt to the viewing method to be easier to read for visually impaired users.
h4 - Structure
p - Responsive Design: Ensure that your website or application adapts to different screen sizes and orientations to provide an optimal viewing experience for all users. This includes maintaining usability on desktops, tablets, and mobile devices. Use flex and media queries to adjust content and layout dynamically. Avoid fixed-width layouts. Be aware that using grid layouts can cause a keyboard navigation disconnect by making the visual layout and source code order different.
h4 - Sensory Characteristics
p - Sensory Elements: Avoid relying solely on sensory characteristics like color, shape, or size to convey information. Ensure text and graphical elements meet minimum contrast ratios by adjusting color combinations using color and background-color properties.
p - Focus: A visible focus indicator ensures keyboard users can navigate interfaces efficiently. There will automatically be a focus indicator when you add a focusable element to your HTML. Do not remove it! Adjust the styles to better fit your design needs. Make sure it has sufficient contrast against other background colors and the background color of the component receiving focus.
h4 - Visual Content
p - CSS can be used to make images easier and less distracting to see. It can also make the focus indicator more distinguishable.
h3 - Best Practices
h4 - Screen Reader Content
p - Sometimes, specific content is needed for screen reader users but not for sighted users. This can be achieved with visually hidden styles. This technique is useful for including long descriptions or detailed explanations that complement visible content without distracting users who do not need this information. This ensures that screen readers announce additional context without displaying it visually.
h4 - Media Queries
p - CSS experts recommend always designing for mobile first! Media queries enable the creation of responsive layouts tailored to different devices and environments. This is a great way to create designs that present well on all kinds of devices because they enlarge, shrink, or wrap content in the available space.
h4 - Focus
p - Avoid relying solely on sensory characteristics like color, shape, or size to convey information. Ensure text and graphical elements meet minimum contrast ratios by adjusting color combinations using color and background-color properties.
h2 - Evaluate
p - This reveals content that is inaccessible but won't guarantee complete accessibility. Continue reading for in-depth accessibility checks and practices.
h3 - Check Accessibility
p - Does CSS use relative units for sizing to aid with responsive design?
p - Does CSS provide visible focus indication for all interactive elements?
p - Does CSS help the responsive design and practices for custom user settings?
h2 - Decide
p - Learn more about what to do with evaluation data and how to pick which content is most accessible.
h3 - Remediation
p - After evaluating your content, you may find several accessibility issues. Prioritize remediating content that has the greatest impact on the user.
p - Once you've decided on the most critical accessibility issues to address, it's time to implement changes. This may involve:
p - Color Contrast: Ensure the contrast between text and background colors is high enough to meet WCAG standards, which is crucial for users with low vision.
p - Logical Hiding: Use CSS to visually hide content (like a "skip to main content" link) from the screen while keeping it available to screen readers.
p - Clear Focus Indicators: Provide a clear, visible outline around elements when they receive keyboard focus. This is essential for users who navigate with a keyboard.
p - Responsive and Scalable Design: Use relative units like rem and em for sizing to allow text and layouts to scale with user preferences without breaking the design.
p - For more help request accessibility assistance for your content or schedule a training with a specialist, in person or online. These trainings can be as quick as 15mins or as long as an hour. They will teach you more about creating accessible content and answer additional questions you may have.


---End of Page---
---Beginning of Page---

title - Common Digital Accessibility Terminology
h2 - Key Terms
p - Digital Accessibility - The practice of ensuring equally effective and equally integrated functionality, interaction with, and access to digital content for all otherwise qualified users with substantially equivalent ease of use.
p - Digital Content - Information or data accessed on or shared through a computer or other electronic information technology (EIT), including digital sensory experiences. Examples include documents, emails, web pages, courses, multimedia, and software.
p - Electronic Information Technology (EIT) - Equipment or systems that process and communicate information or data in various forms, including the creation, manipulation, storage, transmission, or acquisition.
h2 - Other Terms
p - Accessible - A person with a disability is afforded the opportunity to acquire the same information, engage in the same interactions, and enjoy the same services as a person without a disability in an equally effective and equally integrated manner, with substantially equivalent ease of use.
p - Accommodation - An adaption or adjustment to meet the needs of an individual.
p - Assistive Technology - Any item, piece of equipment, software program, or product system that is used to increase, maintain, or improve the functional capabilities of persons with disabilities.
p - Audio Description - A narration added to the soundtrack to describe important visual details that cannot be understood from the main soundtrack alone.
p - Clean Verbatim - Audio transcription or captions exactly matching the original format with excess fillers omitted and minor grammatical errors removed if it will substantially improve the experience.
p - Descriptive Transcript - A direct alternative format of video, not generally used alongside or with a video. The descriptive transcript can be used independently of the video and the user should receive the same information and engage in an equivalent experience as if they watched the video.
p - Equally Effective Alternative Access - An alternate format, medium, or other aid that provides equal access to digital content when the original does not and cannot be remediated to provide an accessible experience.
p - Parallel - In the context of digital content, structure of items (list items, headings, etc.) should be similar, including: grammar, tense, length, and punctuation.
p - Semantic - In this context, a computer can interpret the meaning; or that the meaning is interpretable by technology.
p - Universal Design for Learning (UDL) - A flexible teaching approach that provides multiple ways for students to access and engage in the learning process
p - Usable - The ability for users to achieve the specified or intended goals effectively, efficiently, and satisfactorily.
p - Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG) - Normative and informative components to guide the design of more accessible web and digital content; developed through the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) process as part of the Web Accessibility Initiative (WAI).


---End of Page---
---Beginning of Page---

