title - Create Digital Content with Accessibility
p - This page covers how to build accessibility into different forms of digital content. This includes overarching principles and help creating a plan for your work. This is important for content creators and instructors.
h2 - Creating with Accessibility
p - Creating with accessibility means building digital content that can be used and understood by as many people as possible, regardless of ability. Across all formats the same basic principles apply. Because the range of tools and platforms is so wide, developing a personal scope is important. By mapping out how you create, share, and collaborate on digital materials, you can identify where digital accessibility practices matter most in your daily work and start applying them consistently from the beginning.
h2 - What is Digital Content?
p - Digital Content is information or data accessed on or shared through a computer or other electronic information technology (EIT), including digital sensory experiences.
p - Here is a list of common digital content:
p - Webpages
p - Documents (PDF, Word, Excel, PowerPoint, etc.)
p - Emails
p - Videos and Images
p - Courses
p - Electronic Books and Databases
p - Software
p - Audio Files
p - We all have a different digital environment depending on our work position and lifestyle. This page will help you define what digital content you use and how to create a digital accessibility plan to prioritize what content needs attention.
h2 - Your Digital Environment
p - Follow the directions to create a list of all your digital content and determine what the top priorities are. You can use this list to organize what you need to learn first or what trainings will be required.
h3 - List Your Digital Environment
p - We each have a unique digital environment with content that requires accessibility. The goal of this section is to make a comprehensive list of all the digital content you use, especially content that is shared with multiple people. Based on your role, you may write down different types of digital content. For example, an instructor might write down Canvas (or LMS), emails, documents, videos, and more. A developer might write software, websites, email, etc. Make this list as extensive as possible.
p - There is a “Personal Digital Content” document that lays out a system for listing content and prioritizing it. Feel free to download a copy of this document to help create your own scope:
p - The following questions will help you identify what content you use regularly. Add any addition platforms or formats to your list.
p - How do you document and record your work? - Think about the tools you use to create and save your work, such as Word documents, PDFs, spreadsheets, software services, or notes in shared drives. The formats you choose and the way you structure information determine how easily others can access and use your content.
p - How do you share content with others? - Consider the ways you distribute information, often through email, cloud storage, websites, or learning platforms. Each method introduces opportunities to make content either easier or harder to access.
p - How do you collaborate on work with others? - Collaboration often happens in shared documents, project management platforms, or version-controlled systems. Digital accessibility matters here too, since headings, meaningful link text, and accessible commenting tools can help all collaborators follow the work.
p - What platform do you use to communicate with others? - Communication platforms like email, chat apps, or video conferencing tools form the backbone of how people stay connected. The platform you choose and how you use it affects who can fully participate.
p - Are you creating resources others access? - If you create resources such as presentations, training materials, guides, or media for others, you are shaping the experience of your audience. Ensuring those resources are accessible means more people can benefit from your work.
h3 - Sort by Priority
p - Now that you have a list of all your digital content, it's time to decide where to start. Here are three priority tiers that explain what is most important. After reading through the priority tiers take a moment to mark your priorities on your digital environment list.
h4 - Tier #1: High Priority
p - High-priority digital content should be made accessible as soon as possible because it directly impacts access to essential information and experiences. This includes materials for students with approved accommodations, course syllabi, newly created digital content, and any front-facing or public content. Making these resources accessible right away ensures equal participation and avoids creating barriers for those who rely on them most.
h4 - Tier #2: Normal Priority
p - Normal-priority digital content should be made accessible, when possible, especially as part of routine updates and maintenance. Examples include content you revise, materials shared outside of your department, resources presented or displayed within your department, and content that is used regularly. Addressing digital accessibility during these natural update cycles keeps it manageable while steadily improving access across your organization.
h4 - Tier #3: Low Priority
p - Low-priority digital content should be made accessible when time allows or when the content is actively used. This category often includes materials borrowed from others or provided by third parties, as well as archived resources kept for historical record. While not urgent, reviewing and improving digital accessibility in these cases still strengthens long-term inclusivity and prevents barriers if the content is reintroduced or reused.
h4 - Exempt Content
p - When content is for personal use only it is exempt from digital accessibility requirements. Examples of this type of content include draft documents, to-do lists, and personal notes. Since personal content won't be shared with anyone, it only needs to fit your accessibility needs. However, it is still a good practice to follow accessibility guidelines and build the habit into everything you create. This also makes the content more user-friendly in general.
h3 - Congrats!
p - Now you have a comprehensive list of all the digital content you use often and where digital accessibility is a priority!
p - Continue to add to this list as new content comes up but take it one step at a time. Looking at the whole list can be overwhelming but remember, not everything needs to be accessible today. Focus on the most important thing and work on that.
h2 - Finding Accessibility Issues
p - Now that you have your digital content list with your priorities, it's time to start with top priority. There are many ways to go about making content accessible. Remember that the Accessibility Services Office is here to help at any time. Contact us to set up a training or get assistance with a specific piece of content. Here are some options on this website to get you started:
p - Visit the Content Formats page to learn more about specific content formats and how to make them accessible:
