title - Deciding on Accessible Content
p - This page covers choosing third-party content that is accessible. It includes how to review testing results and how to understand the risk involved and how to make a plan when challenges arise. This is important for purchasers and instructors..
h2 - Introduction
p - As we think with digital accessibility in mind, there are three things that are beneficial to remember when making decisions for accessibility.
h3 - Barrier
p - A barrier is anything that hinders someone’s ability to use your digital product effectively. By pinpointing the exact barrier, you can prioritize its importance. For instance, missing a keyboard shortcut for a function requires a different fix than unintelligible audio without captions. Many accessibility guidelines, like the Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG), outline specific criteria for different types of barriers.
h3 - Identification
p - Identify how the barrier was discovered.  Specifying the source can help prioritize the issue. For instance, user-reported barriers might require a quicker fix than those identified in an ACR. Additionally, if you have further details about how the issue came to light, including them here can provide valuable context. This could be mentioned alongside the potential violation of a specific WCAG success criterion. By capturing these details, you can gain a deeper understanding of the barrier and its potential impact on users.
h3 - Affected Party
p - The specific needs of the affected party can influence the solution chosen. For example, if the barrier impacts users with visual impairments, solutions like increased color contrast or providing alternative text descriptions become relevant. Try to understand your audience and how content effects those that have visual, auditory, mobility, and cognitive impairments.
h2 - Understanding Risk
p - When we talk about risks in Digital Accessibility, think to what degree our university community be affected because of the inaccessibility our web content has. When a university does not look at their shortcomings, the consequences lead to loss of money and resources but also damage of reputation, loss of interest from potential students with disabilities, and an interruption in the education received by the students in need. If these issues are addressed when a complaint is received, or better yet, we act preemptively to avoid these situations, the expenses made to accommodate the needs of a student or worker are much more preferrable than the process of litigation and loss of opportunities.
p - AAAtraq (Risk Control Program for ADA compliance issues) published an investigation in 2022 that gave clarity on the severity of the situation. If a university does not comply with Accessibility regulations, “up to $6.62 billion in legal demands alone, but this excludes the cost of ongoing monitoring essential to ensure ongoing compliance” could be required from the university. (Website Accessibility Failure: Why Top US Universities Aren’t Doing Enough for Digital Inclusion - AAAtraq.)
p - In the last few years, many institutions for higher education have faced legal actions for failure to abide by these guidelines. This can take the form of lawsuits, threats of taking legal action, government investigations, etc.
h3 - Examples
p - In 2015, two federal class-action lawsuits were submitted by the National Association of the Deaf (NAD) against Harvard University and the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, stating that many of their open online courses did not comply with Title II of the ADA Section 508 because their content failed to provide appropriately accurate and comprehensive captioning. After years of litigation, an agreement was reached where the two schools complied with a settlement to add closed captions or transcripts to all online content and pay $1,575,000 in court costs.
p - Gbossa and Gbossa, “Americans with Disabilities Act (ADA): Is Your Website ADA – Compliant?”
p - A similar case happened in 2014 with the University of Montana, where a complaint was filed by the Alliance for Disability and Students of the University because they could not effectively access the school’s websites or the online class materials with assistive technology. An agreement was reached, and the University took actions to develop procedures and policies, taking every effort possible to make all the web content accessible, train faculty and staff, conducting surveys, along with providing the necessary assistive technology to support the needs of low vision/blind students.
h3 - Calculate Risk
p - Will it be used by the public?
p - Information that can be accessed by the public increases the possibilities of receiving complaints about inaccessible content.
p - Is it required for a class, course, or office?
p - Remember to make content that is adequate for the needs and tools available to the person or department in which it is going to be used.
p - Is it going to be continually used?
p - Will it be used sometimes in a single class? Or many times in a course? Or will it be required daily?
p - Is there a barrier in the content?
p - Can I clearly see what I need to fix in my content after making the adequate tests?
h2 - Selecting a Content Format
p - Even if you do not plan to share content right away, continue to follow best practices to make it accessible. No matter what format you are working with, you must make it accessible for those who need it when requested within 1 business day. We recommend using accessible webpages when possible. PDFs should be a last resort format unless printing is a primary concern. Even if providing a print-ready PDF, consider also including the content in another appropriate format.
p - The following questions are intended to guide you to the most appropriate format. They may not be applicable or useable in all scenarios. Through the list if the answer is yes, move to the next level for the format suggestion. If the answer is no, move to the next question at the same level.
p - Will the content be updated?
p - HTML
p - Do you anticipate it being used on a mobile or tablet device?
p - HTML or EPUB
p - Could it be a webpage?
p - HTML
p - Is it primarily text and was created as a text document?
p - Accessible source document
p - Is it created as a presentation format?
p - Accessible source document
p - Is it a multimedia format?
p - Video and audio?
p - Accessible source file
p - Audio- or video-only?
p - Accessible source file with transcript
p - Consult with Accessibility Services on best format
h2 - Unexpected Challenges
p - It isn't possible to prepare for every type of disability and accommodation need. You may come across unexpected situations when you miss an issue, or the resources and time to work with the adequate tools for accessibility are not available at the moment; do not panic, in these cases a contingency plan needs to be proposed. This is called an Equally Effective Alternative Access Plan (EEAAP) that establishes a different and appropriate way to access the information and set a plan that can be continuously maintained and supervised.
p - This plan is a supplement for when current software or content cannot support all digital accessibility needs. It means users may not have an equal and equivalent experience, but it is intended to provide an equally effective experience. It will give alternative access to the experience or learning outcome so people with disabilities can obtain the necessary tools and knowledge to participate in their professional and academic activities. It acknowledges that you are aware of the potential shortcomings and that you are making the commitment to including everyone.
h3 - Creating an EEAAP
p - Creating an Equally Effective Alternate Access Plan (EEAAP) begins with understanding why the plan is needed and who it will serve. The first step is identifying barriers that prevent individuals with disabilities from fully and independently using a digital product, service, or technology. This is typically done through accessibility evaluations, user testing, or review of vendor documentation such as a VPAT/ACR. Once barriers are identified, the plan should outline alternative solutions that will provide equivalent access to the same information, services, or activities. These solutions may include temporary workarounds, alternative formats, or support from staff while long-term fixes are pursued.
p - An effective EEAAP also requires defined roles and responsibilities. Accountability must be assigned so that every part of the plan has an owner, whether it is monitoring the vendor’s progress, collecting user feedback, or implementing alternative access solutions. The plan should be reviewed and updated regularly to ensure it remains relevant and effective. Finally, communication is critical. The EEAAP should be shared with all appropriate parties, including faculty, staff, students, vendors, and disability services, so that access is consistently provided in a timely manner.
h3 - Components of an EEAAP
h4 - Plan Creator
p - This section identifies the individual or office responsible for creating the EEAAP. It should include the creator’s name, role or title, department, and full contact information. This ensures accountability and provides a direct point of contact for questions or updates about the plan. If multiple people are involved, list each with their responsibilities clearly defined.
h4 - Example
p - Name: Jane Doe
p - Title: Director
p - Department: Office of Information Technology
Email: jdoe@college.edu | Phone: (555) 555-5555
h4 - Technology Information
p - This section describes the technology or digital resource that the EEAAP covers. Include the product name, version number (if applicable), vendor/provider, and a description of its primary use or purpose. Note who will be using the technology (e.g., students, faculty, staff, or the public) and identify the specific accessibility barriers that exist. Clearly state why the technology is necessary and cannot be replaced by a more accessible alternative.
h4 - Example
p - Product Name: MathPro Online Homework Platform (Version 3.2)
Description: A web-based platform that allows instructors to assign and grade homework and students to submit and complete assignments.
Purpose/Use: Used in all introductory math courses for homework and grading.
User Group: Students and Faculty
Scope: Department-wide (Math)
Lifecycle: Adopted in Fall 2025 with a five-year contract.
Accessibility Barriers: The built-in equation editor is not compatible with screen readers, and graphing tools have low color contrast.
h4 - Vendor Information
p - Document the vendor’s name, role in providing the technology, and their contact information. Include any accessibility documentation provided by the vendor (such as a VPAT/ACR) and specify whether the vendor has agreed to provide digital accessibility improvements or timelines. This section should also clarify the responsibilities of the vendor versus the institution in ensuring digital accessibility.
h4 - Example
p - Name: EduTech Solutions, Inc.
Contact: accessibility@edutech.com | (555) 987-6543
Website: www.edutechsolutions.com
Accessibility Documentation: ACR provided, dated March 2025. Vendor has committed to addressing equation editor accessibility in the December 2025 update.
h4 - Potential Digital Accessibility Barriers
p - The barrier table is designed to give a clear, structured view of accessibility issues and the steps the institution will take to provide equally effective alternate access. By filling in each part of the table, institutions ensure that digital accessibility barriers are not only documented but actively managed with accountability and transparency.
h4 - Repair Information
p - This section provides a detailed plan for addressing identified digital accessibility barriers. Include a timeline for fixes or improvements, who is responsible for implementing or tracking the repairs, accommodations available to users while barriers remain, escalation procedures if barriers are not resolved in the planned timeframe.
h4 - Example
p - Barrier: Equation editor not accessible to screen reader users.
Repair Plan: Vendor to release accessible version by December 2025.
Institution Contact: Jane Doe, Director (Your department).
Accommodation: Students with screen readers will be provided with an alternative homework submission option (Word or LaTeX documents emailed to instructors). Faculty will be trained on accepting these submissions.
h4 - Reviews
p - List all stakeholders responsible for reviewing and approving the EEAAP. This should include a combination of line management, IT, Purchasing, Web Accessibility Committee member (external use), Human Resources (employee/faculty use), and Accessibility Services Office (student use). Specify how often reviews will occur and how decisions or updates will be documented.
h4 - Example
p - Reviewers:
p - Jane Doe, Director (Your department)
p - Dr. Karen Lee, Chair, Math Department (Faculty)
p - Alex Rivera, Director, Accessibility Services Office (Student Support)
p - IT Representative
h4 - Comments
p - This section outlines a process for ongoing evaluation of the EEAAP’s effectiveness. Include a schedule for reviewing user feedback, digital accessibility testing results, or other data points. It may also provide space for documenting challenges, adjustments, or additional support that may be required over time.
h4 - Example
p - Evaluation: The EEAAP will be reviewed at the end of each semester.
Feedback: Accessibility Services Office will collect student feedback on the effectiveness of the workaround.
Documentation: Comments will be added to this section as accessibility issues are reported or resolved.
