title - Descriptive Transcripts
p - Descriptive transcripts function as a text-based direct alternative to a video or other multimedia. Descriptive Transcript is a direct alternative format of video, not generally used alongside or with a video. The descriptive transcript can be used independently of the video and the user should receive the same information and engage in an equivalent experience as if they watched the video.
p - Unlike regular transcripts or captions, descriptive transcripts include both spoken dialogue, sounds, and descriptions of key visual elements, like actions, characters, scene changes, or on-screen text. A descriptive transcript should include three main components: dialogue, sound descriptions, and visual descriptions.
p - Quality closed captioning can form the foundation of the dialogue and sound description portions of a descriptive transcript. Audio description can form the basis of the visual descriptions of the transcript.
p - The pieces of the transcript should be formatted and structured to be easy to use and understand, including incorporating the aspects and principles of accessibility.
h2 - Dialogue
p - The speech content, or dialogue, forms the backbone of most descriptive transcripts. It captures all of the spoken words. Accurate, verbatim transcription is essential to allow users to fully understand the content and preserve the original message, tone, and intent.
p - Different speakers should be identified in the descriptive transcript. We recommend adding speaker identification to the beginning of the paragraph when a speaker changes followed by a colon.
h2 - Sound Descriptions
p - Details about the non-speech audio elements are included as sound descriptions. These will include things like music, sound effects, ambient noises, and other auditory cues. In captions we are limited to the timing of the video content on the screen and limited characters of the caption box, in a descriptive transcript there are no such limits.
p - We recommend including these in the descriptive transcript in italics and square brackets to off-set them from the spoken content.
h2 - Visual Descriptions
p - Details about the informational or important visual elements are included as visual descriptions. This will include things like actions, gestures, facial expressions, character descriptions, scene changes, on screen text, or other visual cues helpful for comprehension. The goal is to help the visual nuances be conveyed.
p - We recommend including these in the descriptive transcript in italics and square brackets to off-set them from the spoken content.
h2 - Resources
p - Transcripts | W3C
p - Planning Audio and Video Media | W3C
p - Descriptive Transcripts for Time-Based Media | Boise State
p - Transcribing Audio to Text | W3C
h3 - Audio Description
p - Is an audio description track or version available including information about all informational visual content not understood from the main soundtrack?
p - Is the audio description provided in such a way to not interfere with the original soundtrack?
p - Is the audio description synchronized with the video?
h2 - Descriptive Transcript
p - Is a descriptive transcript available in an easy to find location, and logically associated with the video?
p - Does the descriptive transcript include all dialogue, non-speech sounds, and visual descriptions to be a direct alternative to the video?
p - Does the descriptive transcript meet accessibility requirements of the format?
p - Is each speaker identified each time the speaker changes?
p - Does the transcript include logical structure markup?


