title - Emails
h2 - Understand
p - Learn more about the content format and common digital accessibility issues before working with emails.
p - Email is used widely and is a primary form of communication for businesses. Ensuring your emails are accessible broadens audience reach, engages more users, and allows users to feel more included.
h3 - Frequently Asked Questions
h4 - When are emails the best format?
p - Appropriate use cases include professional or business communication, documentation of interactions, mass communications, and legal or sensitive information
h4 - What are the benefits of using emails?
p - The benefits of using this format include efficiency reaching a broad audience at their convenience and optimized for search and finding content.
h4 - What are the limitations of emails?
p - Some limitations include difficulty including complex content (can be worked around by adding an attachment) and too many emails can be overwhelming for some people.
h3 - Recommended Software
h4 - Microsoft Outlook
p - Outlook is an email platform by Microsoft. It is the email that BYU-Idaho students and employees use.
h2 - Create
p - Learn more about creating accessible emails. The Aspects address the most common digital accessibility issues. Following these principles will help make more accessible and user-friendly content. Best practices are “nice-to-haves” in digital accessibility. Focus on these after applying the aspects.
h3 - APPLY THE ASPECTS
h4 - Usability
p - Keep language simple, clear, and concise
p - Ensure all attached files meet the digital accessibility requirements of the format
h4 - Real Text
h4 - Structure
p - Use lists to simplify content
p - Limit the use of tables
p - Use descriptive linked text
p - Tables should formatted for no horizontal scrolling, including on mobile devices
p - Use headings to break up content topics and sections
h4 - Sensory Characteristics
p - Convey all information independent of color
p - Use layout options to add spacing
p - Pair informational sensory characteristics with a semantic partner
p - Ensure color contrast is sufficient between text and background and within images
h4 - Visual Content
p - Add alt text to all visual elements
p - Images, diagrams, and graphics should have descriptive alternative text
h3 - Best Practices
h4 - Technical
p - Run an accessibility check and resolve all the issues if possible. Ensure that any embedded or external resources are accessible as well. If there are other content formats, make sure they readjust on smaller or bigger screens.
h4 - Content
p - Add a short descriptive subject line, this acts like a title or header that organizes your content. Keep the writing simple, concise, and clear. Make sure that all call-to-actions use actionable and descriptive text. If you add contact information, ensure that it is interactive and selectable.
h2 - Evaluate
p - This reveals content that is inaccessible but won't guarantee complete digital accessibility. Continue reading for in-depth accessibility checks and practices.
h3 - Quick Accessibility Check
p - Run an automated checker - Use an automated accessibility checker to review things like color and contrast, images, tables, other structure elements, and access restrictions. If there are any issues, this gives you a good idea of where to start fixing for digital accessibility.
p - Descriptive subject line - Review the subject line of the email for clarity and specificity. The subject should provide immediate context and expectation prior to opening the email.
p - Simple content and structure - Review the language of the email for simplicity and clarity. The email should be simple and limited to basic structure elements when necessary. Lists and short paragraphs can be used to improve navigation and readability.
h2 - Decide
p - Learn more about what to do with evaluation data and how to pick which content is most accessible.
h3 - Selecting Content
p - Accessible emails share many characteristics with accessible websites. They both use semantic headings and HTML structure to display information. Some best practices is to focus on making sure email content uses real text and doesn't have a confusing layout. When deciding on what content to provide, try to ensure that it is appropriately accessible. Here is a list of some things to focus on when providing accessible content:
p - Proper headings
p - Alt text for attachments/embeddings
p - Use plain, understandable language
p - Real text(not images of text)
p - Descriptive subject lines
p - For more help request accessibility assistance for your content or schedule a training with a specialist, in person or online. These trainings can be as quick as 15mins or as long as an hour. They will teach you more about creating accessible content and answer additional questions you may have.
