title - Evaluating Content for Accessibility
p - This page covers testing and auditing digital content for digital accessibility. This includes personal testing, procurement audits, and implementing user feedback. This is important for creators, instructors, and purchasers.
h2 - Introduction
p - When evaluating digital accessibility, there are three main approaches to testing: automated, manual, and user testing. Automated testing uses software tools to quickly scan for common issues, such as missing alt text or low color contrast, and is a useful first step for catching easy-to-spot problems. Manual testing involves a person reviewing content against digital accessibility standards, checking things like heading structures, keyboard navigation, and form labels, which often require human judgment. User testing goes a step further by involving people with disabilities who use assistive technologies in real-world scenarios. Together, these methods provide a more complete picture.
h2 - Automated Testing
p - Automated testing uses computer programs to scan content for digital accessibility issues. Some platforms come with built-in accessibility checkers while others require separate software or extensions. Automated testing primarily focuses on technical and code compliance, particularly standards like WCAG. Automated testing is quick and efficient and can easily be built into a development process. These tools can scan large amounts of content at once and maintain a high level of consistency in how testing is done. Automated testing will not catch every possible error. While it is good for getting an overview of digital accessibility, it often misses detailed issues that aren't noticeable by a computer. Overreliance on automated testing can create a false sense of security so it is better in combination with manual and user testing.
h3 - Built-in Digital Accessibility Checkers
p - Often content creation software will have a built-in accessibility checker. These will look for basic issues like missing alt text, bad contrast, incorrect heading levels and so on. Before downloading new software or moving to manual testing, check to see if there are built in tools available. They will usually be in a settings panel or under a heading called “accessibility” or “review”.
p - For example, Microsoft Office documents have a Check Accessibility under the Review tab.
h3 - External Tools
p - If there aren't any built-in tools available, there are lots of options for downloadable tools. These tools often work like extensions that run in a browser or alongside the app. Each content format has different external tools that are applicable.
h3 - Next Steps
p - Now that you have a basic digital accessibility check of your content, look at the results and fix any issues. If you need help to understand what the results are showing, contact the Accessibility Services Office to set up a quick training or visit the Create page on this website for some basic tips on making your content format more accessible.
p - After solving these issues, move on to manual testing. This will help catch other common issues that a computer will not recognize.
h3 - Automated Testing Tools
p - Note: see the content format pages for more detailed evaluate methods and tools related to each content format.
h2 - Manual Testing
p - Manual testing focuses on the elements that require human judgment and cannot be fully captured by automated tools. Because this type of testing looks at how real people interact with content, it provides important contextual understanding and ensures complex features are evaluated in ways automated checkers might miss. To be effective, manual testing should follow established guidelines and standards, which provide structure and help ensure comprehensive coverage across different types of content.
p - While manual testing offers valuable insight, it also comes with limitations. It can be resource-intensive, requiring time and specialized skills. Results may also vary depending on a tester’s experience or perspective, making consistency a challenge. For large-scale projects, manual testing may be less practical, though it remains an essential part of digital accessibility evaluation.
h3 - Keyboard Only Navigation
p - Keyboard access ensures that users can navigate to, interact with, and access all content using only a keyboard. Many users rely on keyboards to access content. This could be due to disability (physical limitations or visual impairments), temporary conditions, or individual preferences. Keyboard accessibility often improves the design and usability of content for everyone. A few key benefits of creating content that is keyboard accessible include an enhanced user experience, broader audience reach, and cleaner code and structure.
p - The key areas of best practice are focus, interaction, and navigation.
h4 - Focus
h4 - Interaction
h4 - Navigation
h3 - Manual Testing Tools
p - Note: see the content format pages for more detailed evaluate methods and tools related to each content format.
h2 - User Feedback & Testing
p - User testing for digital accessibility provides invaluable insights into how well digital content meets the needs of diverse users. Automated and manual testing can catch many technical issues, but they cannot always reveal the lived experience of someone trying to navigate or interact with a product. By engaging directly with people with disabilities, accessibility testing becomes grounded in real-world experiences rather than assumptions. This approach helps ensure that improvements go beyond technical compliance and actually support usability for everyone.
h3 - Benefits
p - One of the greatest benefits of user testing is authentic feedback. Real users provide perspectives that tools cannot replicate. For instance, students using screen readers, magnifiers, or speech input will show you exactly how your materials function in practice. This helps uncover usability issues that may technically comply with WCAG standards but still cause frustration. User testing ensures that your digital content is not just compliant but also genuinely user-friendly.
p - Another benefit is the way user testing fosters empathy and awareness. When faculty members hear directly from students about what works and what doesn’t, it changes the approach from simply “meeting requirements” to building materials that are welcoming and inclusive. Even small adjustments—such as rethinking a confusing layout or improving instructions—can make a significant difference in student success.
h3 - Getting Started
p - To begin including users in digital accessibility testing, start by looking to your own community. If possible, seek feedback from a variety of students with different disabilities for a wide range of perspectives. Users are the experts in how they use assistive technology so their feedback often highlights barriers that faculty may not notice.
p - Listen carefully to their suggestions and look for patterns in the challenges they describe, such as difficulty navigating course modules, unclear instructions, or inaccessible file formats. Even small changes, like restructuring headings in a document or providing captions on videos, can immediately improve usability. When possible, follow up with users to let them know what changes you have made based on their input. This not only validates their effort in giving feedback but also builds a more collaborative and inclusive learning environment.
p - Visit the Content Formats page for details on creating or fixing inaccessible content or reach out to the Accessibility Services Office for more guided help.
h2 - Laws & Policies
h3 - BYU-Idaho's Accessibility Policy
p - Our Digital Accessibility Policy says:
p - "[Electronic information technologies] used by the University must be accessible to all otherwise qualified individuals, regardless of disability. Likewise, all digital content included in a course, on a web page, shared publicly, or distributed beyond the originating department must be accessible to all otherwise qualified individuals, regardless of disability. … Administrators and staff are responsible for incorporating accessibility in their daily work. … Faculty is responsible for providing an accessible learning environment."
p - In simple terms, this policy means that anything digital created, shared, or used at the University, whether it’s a course resource, a webpage, a video, or a document, needs to be usable by everyone, including people with disabilities. It also clarifies who is responsible: administrators and staff need to make sure digital accessibility is part of their everyday work, and faculty need to make sure their teaching materials and learning environments are accessible. In short, accessibility is a shared responsibility across the entire university community.
h3 - Digital Accessibility Standards at BYU-Idaho
h3 - Legal Requirements for BYU-Idaho
h2 - Procurement
p - The following is general guidelines for accessible procurement practices. Ensure you are following all internal BYU-Idaho policies and procedures with procurement.
p - Accessible procurement involves evaluating the accessibility of digital tools and platforms to ensure they meet the needs of a diverse user base. This process is guided by resources that help assess technology for accessibility and usability. Key standards include WCAG, which define accessibility criteria for web and non-web content.
p - The Information Technology Industry Council created the Voluntary Product Accessibility Template (VPAT) as a template used to create an Accessibility Conformance Report (ACR). It outlines specific accessibility criteria based on recognized standards such as WCAG or Section 508. Because the this is a voluntary process, there is no guarantee how accurate the report is.
p - Before investing in a new product, research and evaluate its accessibility carefully to meet the university's digital accessibility standards and provide a fully inclusive experience. The primary goal of accessible procurement is to select technology that allows all users to perform necessary tasks with comparable ease. This includes assessing usability across all devices and settings (desktop, mobile, etc.) and verifying compatibility with assistive technology.
h3 - Purchase Evaluation Steps
p - Conduct Internal Accessibility Testing
p - Assess Vendor Commitment to Accessibility
p - Look into the vendor’s track record for accessibility improvements and their commitment to future updates that will improve digital accessibility.
p - Determine Need for an EEAAP
p - If the product has known accessibility limitations, determine if an EEAAP is required to provide equally effective alternatives for those impacted.
h3 - Procurement Resources
h3 - Reviewing Reports
p - A VPAT is the blank template that vendors use to report how their product meets accessibility standards such as WCAG or Section 508. Once a vendor fills out this template with actual results, it becomes an ACR. In other words, the VPAT is the form, and the ACR is the finished report that organizations use to evaluate digital accessibility. Since the ACR is the usable version, most people only need to know how to read and understand an ACR. Even though the terms mean different things, they are used interchangeably by many people.
h4 - How to Read a VPAT/ACR
p - An ACR is typically organized into tables. Each table contains a list of digital accessibility requirements, the vendor’s statement of how well the product meets those requirements, and any explanations or notes. The most important column is the one that states the level of conformance. Common answers you will see are “Supports,” “Partially Supports,” or “Does Not Support.” “Supports” means the product meets the requirement without issues, “Partially Supports” means there are some limitations or exceptions, and “Does Not Support” means the product fails to meet that requirement. The remarks column adds detail to these statements, helping you understand what those ratings actually mean in practice.
p - Here’s an example of how part of an ACR might look when based on WCAG 2.1 criteria:
p - When reading an ACR, the remarks are just as important as the conformance level. For example, a product may be listed as “Partially Supports” under the color contrast requirement, but the remarks might explain that the issue is limited to one or two buttons that are rarely used. That might not be a critical issue. On the other hand, a “Partially Supports” rating for keyboard accessibility could mean that an entire section of the product is impossible to use without a mouse, which could be a dealbreaker for some users.
p - Here’s another sample showing how Section 508 criteria might be reported in an ACR:
p - The real value of an ACR is that it goes beyond just saying “yes” or “no” about accessibility. It gives you a clearer picture of how the product behaves in different situations and for different users. By reading the tables carefully, you can determine whether the digital accessibility issues described are small inconveniences or serious barriers. A well-written ACR allows you to make an informed decision about whether the product will work for your audience, and it can also guide you in asking vendors about their plans for fixing accessibility gaps in future updates.
