title - Forms & Surveys
h2 - Understand
p - Learn more about the content format and common digital accessibility issues before working with forms and surveys.
p - Survey and form tools are a great way to collect structured information, feedback, and opinions from an audience. They offer inclusive ways to gather data effectively.
h3 - Frequently Asked Questions
h4 - When are forms or surveys a good option?
p - Appropriate Use Cases include gathering feedback in real time from events, performing registration, sign-ups, or contact information collection.
h4 - What are the benefits of forms and surveys?
p - The benefits include reaching a broader audience with inclusive participation, increased validity of collected data, tailored to have multiple-choice options, dropdowns, or open-text field.
h4 - What are the limitations of forms and surveys?
p - Some limitations include not all question types can be made fully accessible, accessibility features may require manual adjustments, CAPTCHA systems often create barriers for people with disabilities.
h3 - Recommended Software
h4 - Microsoft Forms
p - A simple, user-friendly tool for creating surveys and quizzes. It's part of the Microsoft 365 suite, offering seamless integration with other Microsoft products for quick data collection and collaboration.
h4 - Google Forms
p - A free and easy-to-use survey creator. It's known for its strong real-time collaboration features and quick integration with Google Sheets, making it ideal for fast, simple data collection.
h4 - Qualtrics
p - An advanced, enterprise-level platform for sophisticated surveys and research. It offers powerful analytics and complex logic features, making it the preferred tool for in-depth academic and market research.
h2 - Create
p - Learn more about form and survey creation principles. Applying the Aspects will address the most common digital accessibility issues and make the content more accessible and user-friendly. Focus on the Best Practices after all the Aspects have been applied. They are “nice-to-haves” in accessibility but not as urgent.
h3 - Apply the Aspects
h4 - Usability
p - Allow users to edit and review information before submitting
p - User customizations supported (high-contrast, text size, background color, etc.)
p - Content written at appropriate reading level (recommendation: 8th grade)
p - Include status or error messages that are associated with input area
p - If there are time limits, ensure there is a way to request more time.
p - Include a way for users to submit feedback or get help
h4 - Real Text
p - Text information should be selectable, not be an image of text.
p - The language of the form or survey should be set. This will differ depending on the application being used.
p - Instructions should be included at the start of the survey or in the label of each question. Ensure that the instructions are easy to understand and see.
h4 - Structure
p - Break questions up with sections and/or pages.
p - Use a descriptive title for the form.
p - All buttons should act like buttons, not links.
p - Don't use tables for page layout and design, only to show data relationships
p - Ensure that all links are attached to descriptive text
h4 - Sensory Characteristics
p - Convey information independent of color.
p - Use layout options rather than blank characters for spacing.
p - Dynamically size and space elements for easy activation and user customization.
p - Provide errors, alerts, and warnings with context and explanation.
p - Ensure color contrast is sufficient between foreground and background for all informational content.
h4 - Visual Content
p - Visual elements have appropriate text alternatives
p - Associate input boxes with their questions (differs for different software)
p - The alternatives for visuals should match the context of the question or input field.
h3 - Best Practices
h4 - Technical
p - Any external or embedded resources should also meet digital accessibility requirements.
h4 - Flow & Structure
p - Include a title that is clear and descriptive. The fields and sections should be ordered in a logical and intuitive manner. This includes grouping similar questions together with clear visual and structural separations between groups. On multi-page forms, include a progress indicator, when possible, to help users know where they are.
h4 - Questions & Errors
p - Ensure that fields can be filled out using many different input types (single-point touch, keyboard-only, voice, mouse, etc.). The input field instructions should be placed above the question not just as the placeholder text. Any required fields should be marked using more than just color. Any error messages should provide actionable instructions on how to fix the error. Include no response options (not applicable, prefer not to say, no response, etc.) when applicable.
h2 - Evaluate
p - Walk through a quick accessibility check for content that is already been created to evaluate its digital accessibility. For an in-depth evaluation download the content checklist to get a quantitative score.
h3 - Quick Accessibility Check
p - Check Keyboard Navigation - Use the Tab key to navigate through each form field in order. Ensure that each field is accessible in a logical order. Navigation should move sequentially through fields (name, email, phone), and all fields should be reachable with the keyboard alone.
p - Verify Labels and Instructions - Hover over each field or activate a screen reader to confirm if each input field is clearly labeled and instructions are present. Each form field should have a label or helper text that describes its purpose (“First Name,” “Email Address”). For screen reader users, labels should be read aloud clearly, indicating what information is expected.
p - Run an Accessibility Checker - Use a built-in or third-party accessibility checker tool (WAVE for web forms, Adobe Acrobat for PDFs) to scan for common issues. Review any reported errors or warnings, especially those related to missing labels, low color contrast, and empty fields. Addressing these issues will resolve many accessibility gaps early in the process.
h2 - Decide
p - Learn more about what to do with evaluation data and how to pick which content is most accessible.
h3 - Choosing Content
p - Form/Survey builders will generally be more accessible due to their template format. However, making sure all form fields are labeled and there is appropriate alt text is a must. When deciding on what content to provide, try to ensure that it is appropriately accessible. Here is a list of some things to focus on when providing accessible content:
p - Contains form field labels
p - Clear layout
p - Visible focus indicators
p - Images have accessible alt text
p - For more help request accessibility assistance for your content or schedule a training with a specialist, in person or online. These trainings can be as quick as 15mins or as long as an hour. They will teach you more about creating accessible content and answer additional questions you may have.
p - Feel free to comment your own tips and tricks in the comment section below:


