title - Foundational Knowledge of Digital Accessibility
p - Understanding the basic foundation of digital accessibility is necessary for all people, regardless of their ability or job position. This section covers the fundamental principles of digital accessibility, why it matters, and how to think through content in order to move forward in your accessibility journey.
h2 - What is Digital Accessibility?
p - We define digital accessibility as “the practice of ensuring equally effective and equally integrated functionality, interaction with, and access to digital content for all otherwise qualified users with substantially equivalent ease of use.”
h2 - Why Accessibility Matters
h3 - Our Mission
p - As part of the BYU-Idaho mission, we aim to provide a high-quality education to students of all abilities. Digital accessibility is an essential part of supporting a diverse student body. The Accessibility Services Office assists 5-10% of students. However, data from the National Center for Education Statistics (2019–20) shows that 20.5% of undergraduate students report having a disability. These statistics show a pressing need for accessible accommodations, both digital and physical.
p - This need aligns with our mission to:
p - “Provide a high-quality education that prepares students of diverse interests and abilities for lifelong learning and employment.” (1)
p - Providing accessible content is necessary to fulfill this mission and is part of our responsibility to care for those around us. Accessibility is an essential part of completing this and providing equal opportunity for students to grow academically, socially, and spiritually. We want to support every student on their journey to develop as a disciple of Jesus Christ.
p - To learn more about what digital accessibility means and why it is important, visit our page Understand Digital Accessibility:
h2 - Accessibility Terminology
p - Review a dictionary of common terms used in the digital accessibility world.
h2 - The Aspects of Digital Accessibility
p - The Aspects were created by the Accessibility Services Office as a beginner friendly way to assess digital content. These Aspects fix the most common digital accessibility issues across many content formats. If you only learn one thing about accessibility, we suggest you learn these!
