title - HTML
h2 - Understand
p - Learn more about the basic knowledge needed to work with HTML.
p - Hypertext Markup Language (HTML) is the foundational language used to structure web content. It provides the framework that browsers use to display text, images, links, and interactive elements on a webpage. Properly written HTML supports accessibility by ensuring that content is understandable, navigable, and usable for all users, including those who rely on assistive technologies like screen readers. HTML is at its best when it prioritizes semantic meaning, allowing assistive technologies to interpret and present content effectively.
h3 - Frequently Asked Questions
h4 - When should HTML be used?
p - HTML code is an essential element of any website. All content has to be represented through HTML.
h4 - What are the benefits of HTML?
p - It is easy to build in elements that already have labels and accessible characteristics (i.e. a button element in HTML reads as a button to a screen reader).
h4 - What are the limitations of HTML?
p - Improper nesting or use of elements may confuse technology like screen readers. User errors can cause critical errors and missing information shared
h2 - Create
p - Learn more about creating accessible audio files. The Aspects address the most common digital accessibility issues. Following these principles will help make more accessible and user-friendly content. Best practices are “nice-to-haves” in accessibility; focus on these after applying the aspects.
h3 - Apply the Aspects
h4 - Usability
p - Make sure focus is clear and predictable for keyboard users.
h4 - Real Text
p - The language for the page is specified using the lang attribute in the <html> tag.
h4 - Structure
p - Landmark Regions: HTML landmarks like <header>, <nav>, <main>, <aside>, and <footer> provide a clear structure, enabling users to jump between sections quickly. For example, placing your navigation inside a <nav> tag helps users identify it as the main menu. Similarly, reserving the <main> tag for primary content allows users to skip over repetitive elements like headers or menus. This helps create a logical and predictable experience for those who use some assistive technologies.
p - Table Structure: When presenting tabular data, use the <table> element along with <th> for headers and <td> for data cells. Headers should be connected to their respective rows or columns using the scope attribute, which helps screen readers understand the relationship between data points. Avoid merging cells or leaving rows empty, as these practices disrupt the table's logical flow for assistive technologies.
p - Forms: When designing forms, every input field should have a clear and descriptive label. For instance, instead of simply placing a placeholder inside a field, use a <label> element connected to the input. This ensures that screen readers can announce the purpose of the field, making the form accessible to all users. Additionally, error messages should be dynamically linked to their corresponding fields so users know exactly what needs to be fixed.
h4 - Sensory Characteristics
p - Ensure sufficient color contrast between text and background. Also consider color blindness when choosing colors.
h4 - Visual Content
p - Descriptive alt text for images provided.
h3 - Best Practices
h4 - Semantic Elements
p - Semantic HTML elements (e.g., <button>, <nav>, <li>, <article>) convey the meaning and structure of content to assistive technologies. For example, using <button> instead of a <div> styled to look like a button ensures that keyboard navigation and screen readers can identify it correctly. Avoid using generic containers like <div> and <span> when a semantic alternative exists.
h4 - Strategic Headings
p - Headings (<h1> through <h6>) organize content and improve navigation for users of assistive technologies. They should follow a logical order, starting with <h1> for the main title and avoiding skipping levels (e.g., jumping from <h1> to <h4>).
h4 - Keyboard Navigability
p - All interactive elements, such as links, buttons, and form fields, should be accessible via keyboard. Test your site by navigating using only the Tab key and Enter or Space to interact with elements. Avoid removing native focus styles without replacing them with clear, visible indicators.
h2 - Evaluate
p - This reveals content that is inaccessible but won't guarantee complete digital accessibility. Continue reading for in-depth accessibility checks and practices.
h3 - Quick Accessibility Check
p - Are semantic elements used when one is available?
p - Do all form inputs include a programmatically linked descriptive label?
p - Are related inputs grouped together?
p - Is the language set for the whole and parts as appropriate?
h2 - Decide
p - Learn more about what to do with evaluation data and how to pick which content is most accessible.
h3 - Remediation
p - After evaluating your content, you may find several accessibility issues. Prioritize remediating content that has the greatest impact on the user.
p - Once you've decided on the most critical accessibility issues to address, it's time to implement changes. This may involve:
p - Semantic HTML: Use proper HTML tags to give the page a logical structure that assistive technologies can read.
p - Keyboard Usability: Ensure all interactive elements can be navigated and activated using only the keyboard.
p - Accessible Media: Add descriptive alt text to images and provide captions and transcripts for all videos and audio.
p - Good Contrast: Use a tool to verify that color contrast meets WCAG standards and avoid using color as the sole means of communication.
p - For more help request accessibility assistance for your content or schedule a training with a specialist, in person or online. These trainings can be as quick as 15mins or as long as an hour. They will teach you more about creating accessible content and answer additional questions you may have.
p - Feel free to add your own tips and tricks into the comment section:


