title - Images
h2 - Introduction
p - Images play a valuable role in digital content. They provide a second view of information. However, they can also present unique accessibility concerns and challenges. We will review key points and best practices for accessibility with including images in your content.
p - These principles can be applied to other visual content as well.
h2 - Informative vs Decorative
p - Determining if an image is decorative or informative is the first step. Decorative images are present for visual or aesthetic purposes and do not add any informational value to the content. Informative images convey information to the user and require a semantic alternative to convey that informational value to technology.
p - Here are some questions to help you determine if you image is informative or decorative. If you can answer “yes” to any of these, your images is probably informative.
p - Is the image directly related to the content subject or topic?
p - Does the user miss anything if the image is not present?
p - Does the image communicate specific data to support the content?
p - Is there a clear, defined purpose or message in the image?
p - Would understanding of the content be reduced or incomplete without the image?
p - If an image is decorative, we want to mark it as such so technology ignores or skips it.
h2 - Semantic Alternatives
p - A semantic alternative is how we tell technology the importance and meaning of images. Usually these semantic alternatives will usually be a text-based equivalency to the image. One image might have multiple semantic alternatives and all of the semantic alternatives should be distinct from each other. None of the content in one semantic alternative should be repetitive of another semantic alternative.
p - Semantic alternatives, in combination, should be able to answer the questions:
p - Why is the visual present?
p - What will the user miss with no semantic alternatives?
p - What is visible?
p - Semantic alternatives should not:
p - Provide interpretation or analysis of the image
p - Add additional information not provided visually
p - Repeat information found in the context or other semantic alternatives
p - Omit uncomfortable or controversial content, or any informative visual content in the image
h3 - Alternative Text
p - Alternative text or alt text is a short visual description of the informational value of the image. Every informative image is required to have alt text. Alt text should be the most basic version of what the visual shows. Alt text is limited to a sentence or two (approximately 250 characters or less).
h3 - Long Description
p - Long descriptions are detail explanations about what is visible in an image when it cannot adequately be contained in alt text. There are no limits on how long a long description can be. Instead of including a long description, you may consider adding information to the context of the image.
p - Long description can also include structure, like tables or lists, to help with navigation and organization of content. Long descriptions are particularly useful for complex visuals. Long descriptions can be included in multiple ways and how they are included depends on the content format. Long descriptions should go from the broad information in the image to the details.
h3 - Captions
p - Captions appear in the content visually for all users. They are useful to enhance understanding and purpose of images for all users. They can also provide context or additional information that may be needed to fully understand the visible information in the image.
h2 - Continue Learning
p - Tips for Writing Alternatives
h2 - Resources
p - Images Tutorial | Web Accessibility Initiative (WAI) | W3C
p - Poet Image Description Tool | Diagram Center


---End of Page---
---Beginning of Page---

title - JavaScript
h2 - Understand
p - Learn more about the content format and common digital accessibility issues before working with elements implemented with JavaScript.
p - JavaScript is a programming language that enables interactive web pages. Unlike HTML and CSS, which structure and style a page, JavaScript adds advanced functionality like form validation, dropdown menus, and modals that enhance the user experience. However, when misused, it creates accessibility barriers for people with disabilities.
h3 - Frequently Asked Questions
h4 - When should JavaScript be used?
p - JavaScript can be used to effectively manage focus, announce updates, allow users to modify preferences, and build complex components in websites.
h4 - What are the benefits of using JavaScript?
p - Interactivity
p - Asynchronous content updates
h4 - What are the limitations of JavaScript?
p - Using mouse events can exclude keyboard access
p - Single-page applications require proper handling to communicate dynamic changes
h2 - Create
p - Learn more about audio-only creation principles. Applying the Aspects will address the most common digital accessibility issues and make the content more accessible and user-friendly. Focus on the Best Practices after all the Aspects have been applied. They are “nice-to-haves” in accessibility but not as urgent.
h3 - Apply the Aspects
h4 - Usability
p - Focus: Use element.focus() in JavaScript to direct attention to key elements (such as forms, error messages, or menus) when they become active. This helps users who navigate with keyboards or screen readers. Return focus to the initial element when a component, like a modal or menu, is closed so users don’t lose their navigation context.
p - Form Validation: JavaScript is great for validating forms. Accessible validation should provide clear feedback using aria-live to notify users of errors, along with CSS to visually mark invalid fields. This way, errors are announced in an accessible way. Use aria-describedby on form fields to link them to their corresponding error messages. With aria-invalid and aria-describedby, JavaScript can improve form accessibility, allowing users to receive clear, specific feedback when errors occur.
h4 - Real Text
p - DOM Text: JavaScript-generated graphics (like <canvas> elements) shouldn’t be the only way text is presented. Instead of drawing words on a canvas, also update a hidden <span> or <div> in the DOM with the same text. If you’re injecting content with innerHTML or appendChild(), make sure the text is actual HTML text nodes so screen readers can read it.
p - Text Resize: When changing styles with JavaScript, use relative units (em, rem, %) so text scales properly when users zoom in their browser.
p - Dynamic Content: When using JavaScript to update real-time content (like success alerts or error messages), apply aria-live="polite" or aria-live="assertive" to ensure screen readers announce these changes. Roles, such as role="alert" or role="dialog", allow new content to be correctly identified by assistive technologies.
h4 - Structure
p - Use Correct Tags: Even if you’re adding elements dynamically with JavaScript, create them with the correct tags (still use a button for button elements). This ensures browsers and assistive technologies understand the element’s role without extra ARIA.
p - Reading Order: If JavaScript moves elements, make sure the DOM order still matches the visual layout, so keyboard users and screen readers follow the same sequence.
p - Control Alternatives: Ensure all interactive elements can be activated with both the keyboard and mouse. JavaScript enables keyboard events (keydown, keyup) to add accessibility to buttons, dropdown menus, and other interactive elements. Use CSS to visually highlight focus on these elements (:focus), helping users see which element is currently active.
h4 - Sensory Characteristics
p - Add Error Text: If a JavaScript validation script highlights errors in red, also add text like "Error: Email required" or an icon with aria-label="Error".
p - Color Contrast: When dynamically changing colors via JavaScript, test the new combination with a contrast checker to meet WCAG’s 4.5:1 ratio.
p - Audio Sounds: If you use JavaScript to autoplay sound, also insert pause/stop buttons and ensure they are keyboard accessible.
h4 - Visual Content
p - Alt Text: When JavaScript loads images, set the alt attribute as well. (img.alt = 'Campus map showing accessible entrances';).
p - Captions: If you load video with JavaScript, ensure <track> elements for captions are added or link to a transcript below.
p - Dynamic Element Descriptions: JavaScript can be combined with aria-* attributes to make dynamic elements more accessible. Attributes like aria-live, aria-label, aria-expanded, and aria-hidden help screen reader users understand the content and state of dynamic elements.
h3 - Best Practices
h4 - Dropdown Menus
p - Dynamic menus can be configured to open with both keyboard and mouse. Add click and keydown events (for Enter or Space keys) and use aria-expanded to indicate the menu state.
h4 - Real-Time Alerts
p - Use JavaScript to activate notifications or status messages on the page, such as form submission confirmations. Applying aria-live to the container ensures that screen readers announce the messages without interrupting the user.
h2 - Evaluate
p - Walk through a quick accessibility check for content that is already been created to evaluate its digital accessibility. For an in-depth evaluation download the content checklist to get a quantitative score.
h3 - Quick Accessibility Check
p - Test with Assistive Technology - Open your page, turn on a screen reader (like NVDA for Windows or VoiceOver on Mac), and navigate only with the keyboard. Try interacting with JavaScript-driven menus, modals, and sliders to see if they are announced properly.
p - Automated Checker - run an automated check with a tool like axe DevTools or Lighthouse, then manually test with the keyboard. This catches accessibility bugs before they become embedded in the code.
h2 - Decide
p - Learn more about what to do with evaluation data and how to pick which content is most accessible.
h3 - Remediation
p - After evaluating your content, you may find several accessibility issues. Prioritize remediating content that has the greatest impact on the user.
p - Once you've decided on the most critical accessibility issues to address, it's time to implement changes. This may involve:
p - Focus Management: Use JavaScript to ensure a logical and predictable flow of keyboard focus, especially for dynamic content like modals or pop-up menus.
p - ARIA Live Regions: Implement attributes to alert screen readers when new content appears on the page without a full refresh, such as a validation error or a live chat message.
p - Keyboard Interactivity: Add event listeners to custom or non-semantic elements to make them respond to keyboard input.
p - Custom Components: Use JavaScript to dynamically update ARIA roles and states to accurately describe their status and behavior.
p - For more help request accessibility assistance for your content or schedule a training with a specialist, in person or online. These trainings can be as quick as 15mins or as long as an hour. They will teach you more about creating accessible content and answer additional questions you may have.
p - Feel free to add your own tips and tricks into the comment section:


