title - Learning Management Systems
h2 - Understand
p - Learn more about the content format and common digital accessibility issues before working with Learning Management Systems.
p - Learning Management Software (LMS) is software designed for the facilitation and management of education, classes, clubs, and other university-centered topics. An example of this type of content is Canvas by Instructure, the LMS that BYU-Idaho uses to structure classes and course content.
h3 - Frequently Asked Questions
h4 - When should LMS be used?
p - Appropriate use cases include large amounts of information or course content, training material, and other collections of data than need to be organized and shared with multiple people.
h4 - What are the benefits of LMS?
p - The benefits of using this format include seamless integration into other workflows and software for courses, low-coding method for HTML content, and automatic accessibility implementation for certain content formats.
h4 - What are the limitations of LMS?
p - Some limitations include certain accessibility issues that need to be resolved by the vendor, external or embedded content must meet accessibility requirements as well, third-party software integrated into LMS may not be accessible.
h3 - Recommended Software
h4 - Canvas
p - Canvas LMS is built to make teaching and learning easier for everyone, from the littlest learners to college faculty to business leaders.
h2 - Create
p - Learn more about creating accessible content. The Aspects address the most common digital accessibility issues. Following these principles will help make more accessible and user-friendly content. Best practices are “nice-to-haves” in accessibility. Focus on these after applying the aspects.
h3 - Apply the Aspects
h4 - Usability
p - As you built your content, test that it's still visible and logical if the user magnifies their screen, applies a high-contract theme, or changes their device orientation. Get feedback from students or other users to continuously improve your course.
p - Avoid editing the HTML unless it is necessary and you know how. Changing the HTML can lead to accessibility issues if a creator doesn't know how to change the code correctly.
h4 - Real Text
h4 - Structure
p - Build the navigation so it's simple and logical. All modules, groups and other navigation elements should make sense and follow a hierarchal structure. The language and terminology should be consistent across the course.
p - Every page should have a unique and descriptive title. Page subsections should be created with headings that the text edit provides. This helps a screen reader understand the setup of a page.
p - Do the same thing with table headers when possible. Only use tables to show data relationships not to add layout styling. All links should be descriptive and understandable without other context.
h4 - Sensory Characteristics
p - Convey all information independent of color or sound. For example, don't instruct users to “read the blue text”, or “press the button when they hear a ding.” If sound or color is necessary for an activity, provide another way to perceive it (a popup or text description)
p - Don't use multiple spaces or paragraph breaks. Screen readers will pick up on these and read them aloud. Instead, use the spacing options to create white space.
h4 - Visual Content
p - All visual content should have a description. For an image provide alternative text and for a video provide accurate captions. For graphs and charts, add necessary data into the alternative text or the surrounding text for context.
h3 - Best Practices
h4 - Interaction
p - All interactive elements, like buttons or links, can be accessed using just a keyboard. Review content by pressing the tab key to move between elements and the enter button to activate. All elements should be highlighted when they have focus. Follow this link to learn more about keyboard testing.
h4 - Technical
p - All content has passed an accessibility checker. Any external links to resources have been reviewed for accessibility basic practices. Any feedback from users is implemented regularly to update and improve content.
h4 - Content
p - All content is created with the aspects in mind. This means all visual content has alt text or captions, no pictures of text, all titles and layouts make sense, etc. There are also clear instructions provided before all quizzes, assignments, and discussions. All time limits can be extended or paused.
h2 - Evaluate
p - Walk through a quick accessibility check for content that is already been created to evaluate its digital accessibility. For an in-depth evaluation download the content checklist to get a quantitative score.
h3 - Check Accessibility
p - Run the Automated Checker - use UDOIT and the accessibility checker for the rich text editor in Canvas to identify common digital accessibility issues.
p - Check Images for Alt Text - ensure all images have clear, descriptive alt text that conveys their informational purpose or content.
p - Review Organization and Consistency - Check that headings are in a logical order (H1, H2, H3, etc.). Ensure organization of the course is easy to follow and navigate. Correct any structure or formatting issues that may hinder navigation.
h2 - Decide
p - Learn more about what to do with evaluation data and how to pick which content is most accessible.
h3 - Choosing Content
p - Canvas content has a similar structure to websites. Follow basic practices, such as employing the use of headings and not using images of text to convey information. When deciding on what content to provide, try to ensure that it is appropriately accessible. Here is a list of some things to focus on when providing accessible content:
p - Uses accessible, built in, LMS features
p - Readable with a screen reader
p - Headings and text use proper formatting and tagging
p - No images of text
