title - Moving Images
h2 - Introduction
p - Moving images and animations make content more engaging and fun to use. However, these will require additional considerations for accessibility. Moving images or animations may cause discomfort or health issues for some users. When thoughtfully implemented, moving images and animations can enhance understanding and engagement without causing distraction, discomfort, or distress.
h3 - Examples
p - GIFs (Graphics Interchange Format)
p - Transitions
p - Loading Animations
p - UI Animations
p - 3D Models
p - Scroll Animations
p - Simulations
p - Automatic carousels
h2 - Best Practices
p - Provide an option to reduce motion or a static alternative
p - Test interactive components with a variety technology combinations, including assistive technology
p - Add captions and descriptions to provide a semantic alternative to the informational value
p - Provide stop, pause, or speed adjustments
h2 - Limitations & Cautions
p - Avoid flashing or rapidly changing content (more than 3 flashes per second), provide a warning beforehand
p - Some users may need adjusted timing to read or interact with content
p - Animations and moving images should not be the only means of sharing critical information
p - Animations should be long enough for users to comprehend the information
h2 - Resources
p - Animations | Web Accessibility Initiative (WAI) | W3C
p - Making Your Web Animations Accessible: 5 Tips
p - Animation, Motion, and Timed Content
p - Understanding Success Criterion 2.3.3: Animation from Interactions | WAI | W3C


