title - PDF Documents
h2 - Understand
p - Learn more about the content format and common digital accessibility issues before working with PDF documents.
p - PDFs are a widely used and versatile document format, ideal for preserving layout consistency and ensuring content looks the same across devices. They are commonly used for forms, reports, instructional materials, and archived documents. However, while PDFs can be an effective way to share static content, they come with unique digital accessibility challenges.
h3 - Frequently Asked Questions
h4 - When are PDFs the best format choice?
p - Appropriate use cases include forms, complex tables with limited HTML options, a need to maintain a specific format or layout, creating a document that will never change (such as official documents), or archiving content.
h4 - What are the benefits of PDFs?
p - The benefits of using this format include the possibility of adding tags that make content understandable to the computer, can be used as a digital file or printed file. PDFs are robust or complex documents that maintain formatting, this is helpful for legal documents.
h4 - What are the limitations of PDFs?
p - Some limitations include challenges updating or changing content, time-consuming and difficult to remediate, not conducive for viewing on small screens, such as a mobile device, more work is required to make a PDF accessible.
h3 - Recommended Software
h3 - Adobe Acrobat Pro
p - Adobe Acrobat is one of the only software available for making a PDF completely accessible. Consider downloading it and exploring its features.
h2 - Create
p - Learn more about creating accessible PDFs. The Aspects address the most common digital accessibility issues. Following these principles will help make more accessible and user-friendly content. Best practices are “nice-to-haves” in digtial accessibility. Focus on these after applying the aspects.
h3 - Apply the Aspects
h4 - Usability
p - All elements should be spaced and sized for easy activation. Check that everything makes sense and can be accessed, even in different screen sizes.
p - Review the tag tree and make sure everything is in a logical order. In Adobe Acrobat this option is under Accessibility > Reading Order or Tags. If the document has any links or interactive elements, ensure they can be accessed using just the keyboard (press tab to navigate and enter to activate).
p - When applicable, help or contact information should be placed in the same spot consistently, whether that's on each page or at the end of each document.
h4 - Real Text
p - Set the language of the document. This is different depending on the document format. In Adobe Acrobat go to File > Properties > click the Advanced tab > Reading Options > select the language from the Language dropdown.
p - Create tags for all informational text (this is only possible in Adobe Acrobat). Without tags a PDF can't be made completely accessible.
p - Use the page numbers tool instead of numbering pages manually.
p - Any information that repeats or doesn't add meaning should be made an artifact.
h4 - Structure
p - Ensure that all headings follow a hierarchal structure (H1, H2, H3, etc). There should only be one H1 per document that acts as the title.
p - If there are bookmarks, ensure they match up with the heading structure.
p - Any tables should have marked header cells, as well as a scope when needed. Adding these varies depending on the document.
p - All links should have a OBJR tag. These can be added manual in the Tags panel. However, Adobe Acrobat will automatically add a OBJR (Object Reference) tag to any interactive element that is tagged properly, so double check in the tag tree first.
p - Review that content is appropriately tagged with the correct tag type.
p - If list labels are separate from list item bodies, there should be an alistnumbering attribute applied.
h4 - Sensory Characteristics
p - Information should not use color to convey it's meaning on its own. If color is used to convey meaning, create an alternate way to get the same information.
p - Convert non-informational content to artifact (i.e. multiple blank characters for white space and layout).
p - Use a color checker to check all text and images have the correct contrast ratio.
h4 - Visual Content
p - As with all documents, visual elements must have alternative text. If an image's meaning is already mentioned in the paragraph text it doesn't need to be mention again in the alternative text.
p - Charts and graphs should have meaningful descriptions and data. When needed add additional captions or alternative text to explain the purpose fully.
h3 - Best Practices
h4 - Technical Guidelines
p - Give the file a descriptive title that explains the purpose of the document.
p - If the PDF was converted from another file, ensure that the original file meets all digital accessibility guidelines for its format.
p - Check that all external or embedded resources meet digital accessibility requirements for its format.
p - When the document is finished check it across different devices and resolutions to ensure it is still visible.
h4 - Tag Considerations
p - Field labels should be visual to the human eye and coded so a computer can interpret them.
p - If content spans multiple pages, ensure that the content has a singular tag instead of a tag for each page.
p - When testing a PDF document ignore the pages in the tag tree structure.
h2 - Evaluate
p - This reveals content that is inaccessible but won't guarantee complete digital accessibility. Continue reading for in-depth accessibility checks and practices.
h3 - Quick Accessibility Check
p - Run Automated Checker - Use an automated checker (built-in to Adobe Acrobat, PAC, etc.) to review common digital accessibility issues. Review any errors or warnings. This gives you a good idea of where to start.
p - Review Tag Tree - Use your arrow keys to navigate through each element of the tag tree. Look for appropriate structure tags. Watch to make sure all informational and important content is tagged.
p - Select Text - Select text on multiple pages, select entire pages, select across columns, and so on. Make sure that selected text is in a logical selection order and columns are appropriately marked up.
h2 - Decide
p - Learn more about what to do with evaluation data and how to pick which content is most accessible..
h3 - Selecting Content
p - In general, PDFs are not inherently accessible. All items in a document must be tagged to be legible for those using screen readers. PDFs will need to be manually inspected for proper tags and heading structure, and to make sure that they are usable with a keyboard. When deciding on what content to provide, try to ensure that it is appropriately accessible. Here is a list of some things to focus on when providing accessible content:
p - Is tagged in order
p - Form fields are tagged as such
p - Visual content has alternatives
p - Decorative elements are tagged
p - For more help request accessibility assistance for your content or schedule a training with a specialist, in person or online. These trainings can be as quick as 15mins or as long as an hour. They will teach you more about creating accessible content and answer additional questions you may have.
p - Feel free to add your own tips and tricks into the comment section:


