---Beginning of Page---

title - Presentations
h2 - Understand
p - Learn more about the content format and common digital accessibility issues before working with presentations.
p - The presentations format covers all parts of a presentation, from the displayed materials, speaker delivery, and shared media. We highly recommend for presenters to write a speaker script prior to presenting materials to assist with flow, limited filler words, and ensure that accessibility deliver practices have been considered.
p - Presentation display materials can be achieved with a variety of formats, including: Microsoft PowerPoint, Google Slides, Canva presentations, PDF, HTML, and so on. Some of these are more accessible and easier to make accessible than others. Use your best judgement when choosing your format for displayed materials.
h3 - Frequently Asked Questions
h4 - When should presentation be used?
p - Presentations are best for educational settings with a broad or unknown audience needs, trainings and workshops, public events, and virtual meetings and webinars.
h4 - What are the benefits of presentations?
p - Presentations combine supporting displayed materials with live presentation and interaction for real time clarification, they provide multiple means of conveying information, and display materials can support and help control presentation pace, clarity, and organization.
h4 - What are the limitations of presentations?
p - When giving a presentation trying to be clear and concise may oversimplify complex concepts, cluttered and overfilled displays can cause confusion and overwhelm for audience, and inconsistent pace may not allow for processing and understanding.
h3 - Recommended Software
h4 - Microsoft PowerPoint
p - A feature-rich presentation software with extensive tools for professional slide shows. It provides robust control over animations, transitions, and multimedia, making it a powerful tool for complex presentations.
h4 - Google Slides
p - A free, web-based presentation tool known for its real-time collaboration. It allows multiple users to work together seamlessly and is an excellent choice for simple presentations that require easy sharing.
h4 - Canva Presentations
p - A user-friendly presentation maker focused on visual design. It offers a vast library of templates and a drag-and-drop interface, making it easy for anyone to create professional-looking and visually engaging slide shows.
h2 - Create
p - Learn more about presentation creation principles. Applying the Aspects will address the most common digital accessibility issues and make the content more accessible and user-friendly. Focus on the Best Practices after all the Aspects have been applied. They are “nice-to-haves” in accessibility but not as urgent.
h3 - Apply the Aspects
h4 - Usability
p - Use consistent and predictable slide organization and design
p - Remove automatic timing and transition animations on shared files
p - Verify the Reading Order and Selection Pane for all slides
p - All text content should show in the outline view, in a logical order
p - Transitions are smooth and not disorienting or distracting
h4 - Real Text
p - Use simple, clear, and short text pieces
p - Use large, clear font
p - Use fonts that are consistent, legible, and accessible to all audiences
p - Text information should be selectable and accurate, not an image of text
h4 - Structure
p - Slides have descriptive titles for their content
p - Slide order reflects a logical progression of ideas
p - Links are easy to interact with from display text or URL as the audience
p - All data relationships are shown with a table
p - The appropriate type of lists are used to group related content
h4 - Sensory Characteristics
p - Convey all information independent of color
p - Keep display materials simple and not overcrowded
p - Verbally describe visual relationships between content
p - Informational sensory characteristics are described by the speaker and paired with a semantic partner in shared files
p - Color contrast sufficient between text and background and other informational components
p - Color choices complementary and easy to distinguish
h4 - Visual Content
p - Verbally describe informational visuals
p - Include long visual descriptions in speaker notes or on a hidden slide
p - Multimedia elements are supported with captions or transcripts
p - Visuals are designed to maintain clarity across different devices and screen sizes
h3 - Best Practices
h4 - Content
p - Write speaker notes to clarify, expand, and explain the displayed content, this is especially beneficial when sharing the presentation with others. Ensure that the information flows in a natural and logical way.
h4 - Design
p - Design the slides so that information is easy to read or see. The text should be large and legible, with sufficient spacing. Fonts should consistent and easy to read. Any visual content should be big enough for the audience to see.
h4 - Script & Delivery
p - Consider writing a script or speaker notes to make sure you hit all the important points. Include a description of all visual content and include what the relationship is or why the information is valuable. Define all jargon, technical terms, and acronyms. Deliver the presentation at a moderate pace, with pauses for the audience to process or ask questions. When a question is asked, restate it to ensure you understand and so the whole audience can hear.
h2 - Evaluate
p - Walk through a quick accessibility check for content that is already been created to evaluate its digital accessibility. For an in-depth evaluation download the content checklist to get a quantitative score.
h3 - Quick Accessibility Check
p - Run an automated checker - Use the Accessibility Checker (review tab) to review color and contrast, media and illustrations, tables, structure, and access. If there are any issues, this gives you a good idea of where to start.
p - View display content in greyscale - Set the slides to greyscale (accessibility tab) and confirm color contrast is sufficient. Double check that color is not the only method of conveying meaning.
p - Skim speaker script for flow - Use the speaker script to identify flow of presentation. Double-check there are logical pauses and room for questions, concepts build progressively, and content per slide is consistent.
h2 - Decide
p - Learn more about what to do with evaluation data and how to pick which content is most accessible.
h3 - Selecting Content
p - Presentations will often come in a variety of formats and filetypes. If slideshows follow good file conventions or are based off of predefined templates, they should be usable with a screen reader. Annotating a slideshow and making sure charts and graphs have good alt text/long description is vital. When deciding on what content to provide, try to ensure that it is appropriately accessible. Here is a list of some things to focus on when providing accessible content:
p - Images and graphs have effective alt text and/or long descriptions
p - Color is not the only method of displaying information
p - Sufficient contrast
p - Helpful annotations
p - Transcriptions for the audience can be beneficial
p - For more help request accessibility assistance for your content or schedule a training with a specialist, in person or online. These trainings can be as quick as 15mins or as long as an hour. They will teach you more about creating accessible content and answer additional questions you may have.
