title - Real Text
h2 - The Principle
p - If something looks like text and is meant to be read as text, it should be real text—not an image of text.
p - Real text ensures people and technology can understand and interact with content. Often those with disabilities rely on assistive technologies, like screen readers, for more information. When text is presented as an image, screen readers cannot interpret or read it aloud, creating a barrier for users who depend on these tools.
h3 - Incorrect: Image of Text
p - In addition to being unreadable for a screen reader, images of text can be unclear for users that apply magnification or contrast themes.
h3 - Correct: Textbox
p - It is better to use actual text for any kind of written content. This includes math and writing in other languages.
p - University
h2 - How to Apply
h3 - Language of Page
p - Text needs to be defined so the computer knows what language is being used. This is especially important when more than one language is used. How to do this will vary depending on the format of content.
h3 - Avoid Scans
p - Scanned files are the same as images of text and cannot be read by a screen reader. If possible, start from the original document to create an accessible version. If no digital original exists, make sure the scanned file is a clean, high-quality scan. Then work to make the scanned version accessible. Also consider other sources that convey the same information.
h3 - Customizable Text
p - Users should be able to customize and consume text in their preferred manner. Some users may need to change the font, size, or spacing of the text. Others may have technology read it aloud. Consider how your design is affected by different text.
h3 - Avoid Using Characters for White Space
p - Avoid using the space bar or enter to create white space. These create unseen characters that a screen reader will pick up. Rather, use the built-in spacing settings for paragraphs and line spacing.
h3 - Math Real Text
p - Avoid using images of any math equations or other scientific characters. Instead find programs that display these as interactive elements. For example, math can be included as an interactive element using MathML.
p - Real text ensures that all characters can be interpreted by a computer. This helps people with screen readers to understand all the information on a page. It also provides more consistent digital content.
