title - Sensory Characteristics
h2 - The Principle
p - A user should not need to hear or see to understand or interact with content. Sensory characteristics (even in combination) should not be the only means to understand, operate, or interact with content. Sensory characteristics include location, sound, color, shape, size, and orientation. Each of these on their own can be limiting. But when combined with information the computer can recognize, they provide additional dimension to our content.
h2 - Color Best Practices
p - Contrast - Contrast refers to the difference between the foreground and background colors. If colors are two similar, it can make it harder to perceive. ratios are used to determine if the contrast is high enough. Sufficient contrast is defined as
p - 4.5:1 for normal text
p - 3:1 for large text or user interface components (large text is defined as 14 pt and bold or 18 pt or above.)
p - Combinations - Color blindness and other color deficiency disorders may make it hard to tell certain color combinations apart. There are many different types of color blindness and color deficiency disorders. High-contrast, patterns, shapes, and labels can all be helpful to use alongside color to help relieve this concern. It's helpful to view content in greyscale to verify that color is not the only way information is conveyed.
h3 - Color Button Example
p - Incorrect Use of Color - color should not be the only way to identify the instructed actions.
p - Correct Use of Color - color should be paired with text both in the instructions and in the button (or other action).
h2 - Orientation Best Practices
p - Orientation refers to the way content is displayed. There are two main types: portrait and landscape. Content should be designed to work with either orientation. Here are a few important reasons:
p - Large Text - some users may enlarge the font size. When this happens, they should be able to navigate without two-dimensional scrolling (horizontal and vertical) because it can become very tedious, and the content can be hard to understand. Text should reflow to fit the screen size.
p - Fixed Devices - some users in wheelchairs have their devices fixed to their chair in one orientation and if the content does not reflow to that orientation your content may not be usable by them.
p - Consistency - some users may be confused if content automatically switches to a specific orientation. Keeping content fluid to match their current orientation removes this unexpected change.
h2 - Location Best Practices
p - Content needs to be easy to locate. This is particularly important when content is referenced in other places.
p - Locating Elements - If you reference a diagram on the left but the user has enlarged the content or changed the orientation, the diagram might appear in another spot. Instead of using the location as a reference, try using the diagram caption or title.
p - Navigation - navigation menus and help should be in a consistent location throughout your content to make them easy to find. This helps users navigate effectively without spending extra time trying to understand the setup.
p - Sensory Characteristics aspect helps users understand content even if they can't see color or hear sound. It also ensures users can apply different settings to their devices and still navigate content effectively.
