---Beginning of Page---

title - Software
h2 - Understand
p - Learn about the content format and common digital accessibility issues before moving forward.
p - Developing accessible software ensures that your product reaches the audience you intend to use it in a way that they can use it. The format of software specifically talks about software applications (mobile or desktop).
h3 - Frequently Asked Questions
h4 - What uses does software formats have?
p - Appropriate use cases include offline access, long-term cost and stability, low-latency performance, legacy integration, and regulatory compliance.
h4 - What are the benefits of software?
p - The benefits include improved usability and user experience for everyone, expanded market reach, enhanced brand reputation, improved search and indexing functionality, cost reduction to design and develop with accessibility from the beginning of the process.
h4 - What are the limitations of software?
p - Some limitations include resource-intensive testing and quality assurance for compliance, risk of overcomplex design, communication and annotation mistakes between design and development, over-simplification may alienate advanced users.
h2 - Create
p - Learn more about software creation principles. Applying the Aspects will address the most common digital accessibility issues and make the content more accessible and user-friendly. Focus on the Best Practices after all the Aspects have been applied. They are “nice-to-haves” in accessibility but not as urgent.
h3 - Apply the Aspects
h4 - Usability
p - Software should be responsive to user customization (screen size, magnification, accessibility settings, auto-fill, etc.)
p - Communicate and associate error and status messages (semantically and visually)
p - Users can submit accessibility barriers and feedback
p - All content can be accessed and interacted with various input types without traps.
p - Focus is predictable, visible, and logical.
h4 - Real Text
p - Clearly annotate designs and wireframes.
p - Make text selectable and accurate.
p - Set the language when possible and needed.
p - Add comments to code to aid in debugging and future updates.
h4 - Structure
p - Pages and dialogues have descriptive and unique names.
p - Different structural elements are consistent and unique from other elements and used as they are intended.
p - Group similar items together.
h4 - Sensory Characteristics
p - Convey all information independent of color.
p - Dynamically size and space elements for customization and easy of activation.
p - Pair informational sensory characteristics with a semantic partner.
p - Color contrast should be sufficient between foreground and background colors of informational content.
p - Form labels are associated visually and semantically with their input.
h4 - Visual Content
p - All meaningful visuals (videos, images, diagrams, etc.) have an appropriate semantic alternative (alt text, long description, descriptive transcript, etc.)
p - Functional visuals (links, buttons, etc.) should have a semantic alternative that conveys their function.
h3 - Best Practices
h4 - User Interface
p - Is the application designed to be usable on various screen sizes, resolutions, orientations?
p - Are custom controls and elements designed with digital accessibility in mind?
p - Are keyboard shortcuts available and customizable by users?
p - Are inputs provided with visual and semantic instructions, hints, or tips?
p - Can actions be reviewed or edited before finalization or undone after?
h4 - Technical
p - Does the application support devices accessibility settings on all platforms supported?
p - Has an accessibility conformance report been completed?
p - Do external and embedded resources meet accessibility requirements of the format?
p - Is the code annotated with notes including accessibility behaviors?
p - Does documentation include accessibility information?
h2 - Evaluate
p - Walk through a quick accessibility check for content that is already been created to evaluate its digital accessibility. For an in-depth evaluation download the content checklist to get a quantitative score.
h3 - Quick Accessibility Check
p - Run automated accessibility tests - Use a linter or other automated accessibility testing tools to check for code-based accessibility problems. If there are any errors or warnings, this gives you a good idea of where to start fixing digital accessibility.
p - Keyboard and Focus - Use the Tab key to move through the application. Ensure you can access all interactive elements and that each receives visible focus. Pay attention to the order of elements.
p - Check Color Contrast - Look for any text or UI components that are hard to read due to poor contrast with the background or size. Ensure all states of all elements retains sufficient contrast from other states.
h2 - Decide
p - Learn more about what to do with evaluation data and how to pick which content is most accessible.
h3 - Selecting Content
p - Software accessibility can be more difficult to determine. Generally, widely used and well-known software will be No suggestions more accessible. It is also worth checking out what accessibility tools exist in the settings of the software if they exist. Those can be a good indicator to see what the software offers and if accessibility is taken seriously. When deciding on what content to provide, try to ensure that it is appropriately accessible. Here is a list of some things to focus on when providing accessible content:
p - Keyboard navigable
p - Compatibility with screen readers
p - All non text content has an accessible, text-based alternative
p - Accessibility tools and settings exist
p - For more help request accessibility assistance for your content or schedule a training with a specialist, in person or online. These trainings can be as quick as 15mins or as long as an hour. They will teach you more about creating accessible content and answer additional questions you may have.
