title - Spreadsheets
h2 - Understand
p - Learn about the content format and common digital accessibility issues before moving forward.
p - Spreadsheets are a useful tool to organize, analyze, store, and share data. Spreadsheets typically include data organized in rows and columns and generally allow data to be added, manipulated, and visualized in different ways. Spreadsheets are especially helpful in organizing large or complex data outside of a database.
h3 - Frequently Asked Questions
h4 - When are spreadsheets the best format to use?
p - Appropriate use cases include structured data, static data to share with others, complex calculations, raw data shared, collaboration with data, not complex or large enough to need a database.
h4 - What are the benefits of using spreadsheets?
p - The benefits include better user experience for everyone (navigation, understanding, editing, consistency), improved collaboration, increased reach to those with varying devices and technology.
h4 - What are the limitations of using spreadsheets?
p - Some limitations include content without headers lead to misidentification of content, complexity of data increase's chance for confusion and misunderstanding, not all functions are accessible, planning and design needed before spreadsheet is created
h3 - Recommended Software
h4 - Microsoft Excel
p - Microsoft Excel is a powerful, feature-rich spreadsheet application used for data organization, analysis, and calculation.
h4 - Google Sheets
p - Google Sheets is a free, web-based spreadsheet program that is part of Google's suite of office tools. It is known for its strong collaboration features, allowing multiple users to edit a document simultaneously in real-time.
h2 - Create
p - Applying the Aspects will address the most common digital accessibility issues and make the content more accessible and user-friendly. Focus on the Best Practices after all the Aspects have been applied. They are “nice-to-haves” in accessibility but not as urgent.
h3 - Apply the Aspects
h4 - Usability
p - Remove any blank worksheets.
p - Hide unused columns and rows.
p - Content should follow a logical progression and meaningful order.
p - Formulas and calculations are clearly labeled for comprehension.
h4 - Real Text
p - Use typed text for text.
p - Sheets should have text or content in cell A1.
p - Informational and interactive content should not be protected or restricted.
h4 - Structure
p - Add descriptive names for worksheets.
p - Tables, cells, and ranges should have clear names.
p - Links should be in a cell by themselves and hyperlinked.
p - All tables should have appropriate visual and semantic headers.
p - Lists should be formatted as a single-column table.
p - Links should have descriptive display text.
h4 - Sensory Characteristics
p - Convey all information independent of color.
p - Keep worksheets simple and not overcrowded.
p - Have row heights and column widths adjusted to provide adequate white space.
p - Color contrast should be sufficient for all informational elements.
h4 - Visual Content
p - Include long descriptions of complex visuals in a logical or linked location.
p - Visual elements are positioned logically and are easy to interpret.
p - Charts, diagrams, and graphs include alternative text or explanations.
p - Visualizations are free of unnecessary or confusing clutter.
p - Graphs and charts have a connected accessible table of data.
h3 - Best Practices
h4 - Data
p - Is formatting consistent for numeric values?
p - Is data validation applied when applicable with appropriate error message assistance?
h4 - Organization
p - Did you freeze rows in large bodies of data to assist with navigation and context?
p - Is the structure of each spreadsheet logical?
p - Are instructions, explanations, or help information found in a consistent and logical location?
p - Has metadata been added to identify purpose?
h4 - Visualization
p - Is color supported by a pattern, shape, or label?
p - Are all axes and data points in visualizations clearly labeled with context?
p - Are data visualizations located near or otherwise connected to their data?
h4 - Technical
p - Are unnecessary rows or columns removed or hidden?
p - Did you run an accessibility checker and resolve all issues?
p - Do external and embedded resources meet accessibility requirements of the format?
p - Are all informational cells available to and readable by technology?
p - Has content been reviewed and/or created with the aspects in mind?
h2 - Evaluate
p - Walk through a quick accessibility check for content that is already been created to evaluate its digital accessibility. For an in-depth evaluation download the content checklist to get a quantitative score.
h3 - Quick Accessibility Check
p - Run an automated checker - Use an accessibility checker to review for use of color and contrast, alt text, table headers, merged cells, sheet names, and access restrictions. If there are any issues, this gives you a good idea of where to start fixing digital accessibility.
p - Relational data formatted as tables - Look through each sheet to identify any relational data and check if it is in a table. Verify that each table has appropriate header cell designations and a table title.
p - Text in A1 on every sheet - Look through every sheet in cell A1 to verify there is content. If a sheet is blank, delete it. If it starts farther on the page, A1 may contain instructions or a description.
h2 - Decide
p - Learn more about what to do with evaluation data and how to pick which content is most accessible.
h3 - Selecting Content
p - Spreadsheets can be more difficult to determine accessibility. Tools such as the accessibility checker from Microsoft Excel can aid in finding most common problems. Google Docs doesn't have a built-in accessibility checker, but there is an Add-On called Grackle Docs that can do something similar. When deciding on what content to provide, try to ensure that it is appropriately accessible. Here is a list of some things to focus on when providing accessible content:
p - No merged or split cells if possible
p - Have good color contrast and avoid communicating information only through color
p - Has text in cell A1
p - Alt text for images
p - Straightforward layout
p - For more help request accessibility assistance for your content or schedule a training with a specialist, in person or online. These trainings can be as quick as 15mins or as long as an hour. They will teach you more about creating accessible content and answer additional questions you may have.
p - Feel free to add your own tips and tricks into the comment section:


