title - STEM
h2 - Understand
p - Learn more about the content format and common digital accessibility issues before working with STEM based content.
p - Science, Technology, Engineering, and Mathematics (STEM) is particularly challenging to make accessible. Even with recent advances making content in these fields more accessible, there are still aspects that remain very difficult to convey in digitally.
p - Making STEM content fully accessible will combine digital content techniques, physical or tactile formats, and alternative formats and supplements. It is not as simple as just providing caption and alternative text, but rather ensuring the complex data, diagrams, formulas, code samples, and interactive elements are presented as comprehensively and completely as possible in a combination of mediums.
p - Traditional methods for teaching and presenting math can pose significant challenges for individuals with disabilities. However, designing content with accessibility in mind should help eliminate some of these barriers. The most accessible form of math is MathML, which allows for the creation of interactive math content. However, if no other option, you can add alternative text or another semantic alternative to an image or static representation. It is worth noting that this is the only possibility for PDF, so math is never fully accessible in this format.
h3 - Frequently Asked Questions
h4 - When is STEM content most useful?
p - STEM content is best for displaying complex technical information, such as graphs, math formulas, and other technical content.
h4 - What are the benefits of using STEM formats?
p - Benefits include developing a systematic and logical approach to problem-solving, fostering creative and innovative thinking through experimentation, demonstrating the real-world application of theoretical knowledge, and promoting interdisciplinary connections between different subjects.
h4 - What are the limitations of using STEM formats?
p - Most content formats are primarily text-based
p - Subject-matter experts required to provide correct and exact information needed
p - Interactive and virtual lab tools may be inaccessible with assistive technology
p - Adoption of new markup languages is inconsistent between platforms and technology
h3 - Recommended Software
h3 - MathML
p - MathML (Mathematical Markup Language) is an XML-based language used to display complex mathematical equations and symbols on the web. Think of it as the HTML for math. It provides a standardized format that's both structured and semantically meaningful, which makes the content accessible to both people and computers.
h4 - How is MathML Created?
p - You can create MathML in a couple of ways:
p - Hand-coding: You can write the markup yourself.
p - Using tools: You can use software like the MathType equation editor, which generates the MathML code for you.
h4 - The Role of MathJax
p - While MathML provides the structure, it needs a way to be displayed correctly. This is where MathJax comes in. MathJax is a JavaScript display engine designed specifically for mathematics that ensures math content looks right in all browsers.
p - Some applications, like the Canvas Rich Content Editor (RCE), use LaTeX code and then translate it into MathML. MathJax then takes this MathML and renders it properly, so what you see is a well-formatted equation, not a string of code.
h3 - LaTeX
p - LaTeX is another popular tool for typesetting complex mathematical formulas and equations. While traditionally used in academic research and scientific writing, LaTeX is also a valuable tool for creating accessible math content in digital formats. When used properly, LaTeX can be combined with screen reader-friendly tools to ensure that math content remains accessible.
h3 - Microsoft Word Equations
p - Microsoft Word includes a built-in equation editor that supports the creation of accessible math content, though it’s important to follow best practices to ensure compatibility with screen readers and other assistive technologies. There is a gallery of prebuilt equations that you can chose from, or you can write your own equations and add them to the gallery.
h3 - Canvas Rich Content Editor (RCE)
p - You use the RCE to add content, structure, and formatting to Canvas. You have two different options for adding accessible math.
h4 - Using LaTeX in RCE
p - In your Canvas course, navigate to the location where you want to include math content.
p - Click on Insert Math Equation (under More or the Insert menu) in the RCE.
p - Toggle Directly Edit LaTeX on, and start writing the content in the input field.
p - Always preview your content to ensure that the math renders correctly before publishing.
p - This adds an image of the math in the RCE with the LaTeX as alt text. But when the page is saved, the math is rendered using MathML and MathJax.
h4 - Using MathML in RCE
p - In your Canvas course, navigate to the location where you want to include math content.
p - Click on the HTML editor button in the RCE.
p - Add the MathML in the desired location
p - Always preview your content to ensure that the math renders correctly before publishing.
h2 - Create
p - Learn more about STEM content creation principles. Applying the Aspects will address the most common digital accessibility issues and make the content more accessible and user-friendly. Focus on the Best Practices after all the Aspects have been applied. They are “nice-to-haves” in accessibility but not as urgent.
h3 - Apply the Aspects
h4 - Usability
p - Validate Your MathML: Use online validators to check that your MathML is error-free and adheres to standards.
p - Use the Built-in equation editor: Alway utilize the Equation Editor to ensure proper formatting and accessibility.
h4 - Real Text
p - Keep Equations Simple: Use clear, concise LaTeX code to represent basic formulas and equations. Avoid overly complex notation that may confuse screen reader
p - Use Semantic Markup: Ensure that your LaTeX code is logically structured to enhance accessibility. For example, use proper fractions (\frac) instead of attempting to create fractions using slashes.
h4 - Structure
p - Semantic Structure: When creating math using MathML, make sure that every element (e.g., fractions, exponents, roots) is properly tagged with the corresponding MathML element. This ensures that technology can interpret the structure and meaning of the equation.
p - Maintain Consistency: Use consistent formatting across all math content to help students recognize patterns.
h4 - Sensory Characteristics
p - For Visual Information: Don't use color alone. If you highlight something in red, also use bold text or an asterisk. For images, graphs, or complex diagrams, provide a text description or a data table.
p - For Audio Information: Always provide captions or a transcript for videos and podcasts. This ensures that someone who can't hear the audio can still get all the information.
p - For Interactions: Don't rely on spatial instructions like "click the top-right button." Instead, use clear labels like "Click the 'Submit' button." This allows users with motor or cognitive impairments to navigate easily.
h4 - Visual Content
p - Include Descriptive Text: Provide text descriptions of complex equations to aid understanding for users.
p - Textual Descriptions: Provide a brief description of the equation's significance or context to support understanding.
h2 - Evaluate
p - Walk through a quick accessibility check for content that is already been created to evaluate its digital accessibility. For an in-depth evaluation download the content checklist to get a quantitative score.
h3 - Quick Accessibility Check
p - Accessible Encoding: Verify that equations and formulas are encoded with MathML or LaTeX, not as images, so screen readers can interpret them.
p - Descriptive Alternatives: Ensure all graphs, charts, and diagrams have a detailed text description or an accessible data table.
p - Structured Content: Confirm that content is organized with proper headings and lists for clear navigation.
h2 - Decide
p - Learn more about what to do with evaluation data and how to pick which content is most accessible.
h3 - Choosing Content
p - When deciding on what content to provide, try to ensure that it is appropriately accessible. Here is a list of some things to focus on when providing accessible content:
p - Uses MathML for formulas and equations
p - Well structured, using headings and lists
p - Keyboard operable
p - Has good alt text and long descriptions for diagrams
p - For more help request accessibility assistance for your content or schedule a training with a specialist, in person or online. These trainings can be as quick as 15mins or as long as an hour. They will teach you more about creating accessible content and answer additional questions you may have.
p - Feel free to add your own tips and tricks into the comment section:


