title - Structure
h2 - The Principle
p - The structure of our content should provide a clear and logical framework that enhances a user's experience.
p - Headings and titles help organize the content logically and provide navigation points and are helpful for skimming content.
p - Tables effectively show relationships between data.
p - Lists simplify content and enhance readability by breaking content into manageable chunks.
p - Links and buttons are essential for connecting content to other content or actions. By using structural elements correctly, content is significantly improved for all users.
p - Here is an overview of each:
h3 - Headings
p - Headings apply to a wide range of formats such as slide titles, video chapters, spreadsheet names, subject lines, table captions or headings, page titles or metadata, and labels. Whatever the format, headings are used to label and organize content. They should convey structure and organization in a way that people and computers can recognize.
h4 - Best Practices
p - Use Formatting Tools - most text editors will have formatting tools that create headers. Using these tools not only makes it look like a header to the human eye but also tells the computer to mark it as a header. The computer can tell screen readers or other assistive technology what the content structure is. This will also create an outline of your document, when used correctly.
p - Use Precise Wording - Headings should be descriptive, concise, and consistent so users understand the structure easily.
p - Use Hierarchical Order - Heading levels should be used in a logical, hierarchical, and nested order. Best practice suggests there should be one heading level one for each piece of content (per page or per document).
