title - Understand Digital Accessibility
p - This page covers how we can build accessible thinking into our daily workflow and mindset. It includes a basic understand of what digital accessibility is and what principles to use. These are important for everyone to learn.
h2 - What is Digital Accessibility?
p - We define digital accessibility as “the practice of ensuring equally effective and equally integrated functionality, interaction with, and access to digital content for all otherwise qualified users with substantially equivalent ease of use.”
h3 - What it Means
p - Equally effective and equally integrated functionality means that people with disabilities should be able to use the same tools and features as everyone else, without being separated into a different or “lesser” experience.
p - Interaction with digital content refers to how users navigate, click, type, or otherwise engage with content. Digtal accessibility ensures these interactions are possible for people using assistive technologies like screen readers, voice control, or alternative input devices.
p - Access to digital content means that all users should be able to reach and understand the information provided in the same timeframe without barriers that exclude them.
p - For all otherwise qualified users emphasizes that digital accessibility is about removing unnecessary barriers; if someone has the skills or rights to use the content, disability should not be what prevents them from participating.
p - With substantially equivalent ease of use means the experience should be just as usable and efficient for people with disabilities as it is for everyone else, without extra steps, delays, or difficulties.
h2 - Why Digital Accessibility Matters
h3 - Our Mission
p - As part of the BYU-Idaho mission, we aim to provide a high-quality education to students of all abilities. Digital accessibility is an essential part of supporting a diverse student body. The Accessibility Services Office assists 5-10% of students. However, data from the National Center for Education Statistics (2019–20) shows that 20.5% of undergraduate students report having a disability. These statistics show a pressing need for accessible accommodations, both digital and physical.
p - This need aligns with our mission to:
p - “Provide a high-quality education that prepares students of diverse interests and abilities for lifelong learning and employment.” (1)
p - Providing accessible content is necessary to fulfill this mission and is part of our responsibility to care for those around us. Digital accessibility is an essential part of completing this and providing equal opportunity for students to grow academically, socially, and spiritually. We want to support every student on their journey to develop as a disciple of Jesus Christ.
h3 - Not All Individuals Disclose a Disability
h3 - Innovation
h3 - Digital Accessibility Improves Design
h2 - Color Block Activity
p - This activity illustrates some of the issues that people with disability may face. Follow along with the instructions in the video and ponder the questions below.
p - Reflect on the activity you just completed by answering these questions in the comment section:
p - Which version was easier, and which was harder? Why?
p - What connections can you draw between digital accessibility, disability, and this color block activity?
p - Here are some conclusions you may draw:
p - This activity illustrates how conflicting or distracting information can slow down response time. For individuals with disabilities, the input they receive may be partial or distorted, requiring extra effort to fill in the gaps before they can respond. This delay is simply a matter of processing speed and not a lack of intelligence or understanding. That is why it is necessary to provide fair accommodations for some students with disabilities. It levels the playing field by giving them the resources they need to demonstrate what they know.
h2 - Roles with Influence
p - Everyone can make a difference in their own sphere of influence and can contribute to digital accessibility. An individual may fulfill more than one listed role. These are not exhaustive but will hopefully give you an idea of where to get started.
h3 - Content Creators
p - Content creators are individuals or teams who produce or design digital materials in any format, whether for a course, a webpage, public distribution, or internal use. If you create materials for others or are publishing content, you play a key role in ensuring digital accessibility.
h3 - Instructors
p - Instructors are individuals or teams who provide or deliver educational experiences, whether in or out of the classroom. If your courses or learning materials rely on digital platforms, or if you are responsible for selecting materials that others will use for learning, then you play a key role in ensuring digital accessibility.
h3 - Developers
p - Developers are individuals or teams who create or maintain digital software, websites, content platforms, or applications. If you build, support, or update these tools, you play a key role in ensuring that the technology itself is accessible and usable for everyone.
h3 - Purchasers
p - Purchasers and administrators are individuals or teams who select, procure, or approve digital content and tools for use within an organization. If you participate in choosing, approving, or purchasing software, applications, or other digital resources, then you play a key role in ensuring digital accessibility is considered before adoption.
h2 - The POUR Principles
p - To ensure digital content is accessible, BYU-Idaho refers to the latest version of the Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG) at Level AA. These guidelines provide both required standards and other recommendations for designing accessible websites and digital materials.
p - WCAG is based on four principles, often referred to as POUR:
h3 - Perceivable
p - Content must be presented in ways users can perceive. In other words, people must be able to see, hear, or sense the content. This principle is aided by the use of assistive technology that tells a user about the digital content. It is also important that content is easy to notice.
p - For example, any visual or sensory content needs to have a text alternative so users with a vision impairment can still perceive what is trying to be conveyed. For more criteria visit the Perceivable section on the WCAG website:
h3 - Operable
p - Users must be able to interact with content, whether with a mouse, keyboard, or other tool of their choice. Assistive technology like voice access or eye tracking help with this principle. Watch out for content that is timed or asks for user input.
p - For example, all digital content needs to be navigable using just the keyboard. This allows users with mobility impairments to use keyboard alternatives when needed. For more criteria visit the Operable section on the WCAG website:
h3 - Understandable
p - Content must be clear and easy to understand. All content should have a consistent format and defined terms. Content should react as expected and if a mistake is made, there is help provided.
p - For example, a document or webpage needs to have consistent navigation and identification. This means that all links and buttons are labeled accordingly and are consistent across pages. This makes it easier for users with processing impairments to understand the content. For more criteria visit the Understandable section on the WCAG website:
h3 - Robust
p - Users may be using a variety of technology and software. This means content should be compatible with a wide array of tools and technologies. Content must work across different devices, browsers, and assistive technologies.
p - For example, the coded elements on a webpage need to be defined so that different browsers still read the elements the same way. This ensures that all users get the same experience. For more criteria visit the Robust section on the WCAG website:
h2 - The Aspects
p - The aspects are actionable steps based on the POUR principles. We use the aspects to train the campus on the basics of digital accessibility and the common issues users run into. To learn more about the aspects visit the Foundations tab:
h2 - Assistive Technology and POUR
p - Assistive technology (AT) includes the tools people use to interact with digital content in different ways, such as screen readers, screen magnifiers, voice input, switch devices, and captioning tools. These technologies bridge the gap between a person’s abilities and the digital environment, making content usable in multiple formats. When digital materials are designed with accessibility in mind, assistive technology can interpret and present information effectively.
p - The POUR principles—Perceivable, Operable, Understandable, and Robust—work hand in hand with assistive technology. For example, providing alt text and captions makes content perceivable by allowing screen readers and captioning software to convey information beyond sight and sound. Designing for keyboard use ensures that switch devices and voice commands can operate content smoothly. Clear structure and consistent navigation help users understand content regardless of how they access it. And building content to web standards makes it robust, ensuring it works reliably across different assistive technologies and platforms. Together, accessible design and assistive technology ensure that digital experiences are equally effective for everyone.
p - To learn more about assistive technology and what is available, visit our blog and see the article on assistive technology:
