title - Usability
h2 - The Principle
p - Usability checks we are meeting our organization’s definition of digital accessibility—ensuring content is effective, integrated, functional, and available. While the other aspects of digital accessibility focus on making content perceivable and operable by both humans and technology, usability is about bringing all those pieces together in practice. It bridges the gap between technical compliance and human experience, making sure that content is practical and intuitive to use.
h2 - How to Apply
h3 - Planning
p - Whether you are building or buying digital content, consider the accessibility concerns from the beginning and look for options and ideas that solve those concerns.
p - If you are creating content, it is helpful to use content checklists to make sure you cover all the possible accessibility points.
h3 - Testing
p - Incorporate basic accessibility tests throughout development and make sure content can be accessed through a variety of browsers, devices, operating systems, and settings. There are also built in digital accessibility checkers for a lot of content that will point out common issues.
p - For more information on testing visit our Evaluate for Accessibility page.
h3 - Feedback
p - Implement a way to get feedback from users and then incorporate the feedback when possible.
p - Users will have the most interaction with your content and will spot issues that you may miss. Be open to the feedback you receive.
p - Usability will ensure that every user can understand and navigate content, disability or not. It gives an equal ground for learning and fun for everyone.
p - Continue to the next aspect to keep learning:


