title - Video
h2 - Understand
p - Learn more about the content format and common digital accessibility issues before working with video based content.
p - Video is a popular and powerful media format that enables effective visual and auditory communication in a controlled environment. From entertainment to education, video can capture specific moments in time or act as the frame for edited content.
p - For this particular format, the term "video" refers to both video-only and multimedia (video/audio combination) content.
h3 - Frequently Asked Questions
h4 - When is video most useful?
p - Appropriate use cases include storytelling with visual and auditory information, longer content with more involved and complex concepts, and archiving presentations, classes, or lectures.
h4 - What are the benefits of video?
p - Benefits include multi-factor method of consuming visual and auditory content, can communicate a wide variety of different concepts in shorter timeframes, and includes some advantages of audio-focused content while removing contextual limitations.
h4 - What are the limitations of video?
p - Some limitations include far more involved and expensive than other methods, needs quality captions and an edited descriptive transcript to avoid excluding certain audiences, more difficult to share and send due to file sizes, and requires an accessible media player.
h3 - Recommended Software
h4 - Kaltura
p - A private, professional video management platform with a strong focus on accessibility and compliance for organizational use. It provides tools for creating and editing captions, offers robust keyboard navigation and screen reader support, and allows for the creation of audio descriptions.
h4 - YouTube
p - A public video-sharing platform that offers a broad range of accessibility features. This includes automatic and manually-added captions, transcripts, keyboard navigation, screen reader support, and the ability to adjust playback speed.
h2 - Create
p - Learn more about video creation principles. Applying the Aspects will address the most common digital accessibility issues and make the content more accessible and user-friendly. Focus on the Best Practices after all the Aspects have been applied. They are “nice-to-haves” in accessibility but not as urgent.
h3 - Apply the Aspects
h4 - Usability
p - Media player controls can be accessed and activated using various input types
p - Is the media player accessible?
p - Can the video be paused within 5 seconds, if it auto-plays?
p - Can all meaningful content be focused in a logical order?
h4 - Real Text
p - Clean verbatim descriptive transcript provided
p - Accurate, synchronized captions provided
p - Are speakers identified in both the captions and transcript?
p - Have the captions and transcript been edited for accuracy?
p - Is all on-screen text included in the captions or descriptive transcript?
h4 - Structure
p - Clear and logical progression, supported by a script
p - Chapter markers have been added to section the video
p - Provide context to tables verbally
p - Does the transcript use appropriate headings to mark chapters?
p - Does the transcript use appropriate structure elements?
p - Are links interactive with good descriptive text in the transcript?
h4 - Sensory Characteristics
p - Convey all information independent of color
p - Media player controls meet contrast needs for all states
p - Are informational sounds included in the transcript?
p - Is color contrast sufficient between foreground and background of informational content?
h4 - Visual Content
p - Verbally describe all visuals
p - Visuals support narration or audio
p - Are flashes and flickers kept below 3 per second?
p - Does the transcript include a description of all visuals not described in the soundtrack?
h3 - Best Practices
h4 - Sound
p - Is the audio clear, without static or distortion?
p - Is the soundtrack optimized for mono playback?
p - Was a script used to plan the audio and video content?
h4 - Visuals
p - Do visuals support or provide context to the soundtrack?
p - Are flashes and flickers kept less than 3 per second?
p - Are visuals highly visible and not distracting?
p - Are speakers identified, either through the soundtrack, captions, or visuals on screen?
p - Are captions planned for in the placement of visuals?
h4 - Technical
p - Is the media player, including controls and other elements, accessible?
p - Has content been reviewed and/or created with the aspects in mind?
p - Did you run an accessibility checker and resolve all issues?
p - Do external and embedded resources meet accessibility requirements of the format?
p - Do all downloadable files include clear metadata?
p - If the video auto-plays, can it be stopped or paused within 5 seconds?
h2 - Evaluate
p - Walk through a quick accessibility check for content that is already been created to evaluate its digital accessibility. For an in-depth evaluation download the content checklist to get a quantitative score.
h3 - Quick Accessibility Check
p - Captions - Review that captions are available, accurate, and edited, not just automatically generated. Look at the first minute, random middle selection, and last minute of the video. Captions are quality when they are accurate, consistent, clear, readable, and equal.
p - Alternatives - Review for a descriptive transcript and audio description. Audio description (alongside the audio track) and the descriptive transcript (on its own) should provide an equivalent experience to watching the video. Additional audio description may not be needed if provided in the audio track.
p - Keyboard control - Use the Tab key on your keyboard to check that all video controls can be accessed without the mouse. Use Enter or Spacebar to activate a video control.
h2 - Decide
p - Learn more about what to do with evaluation data and how to pick which content is most accessible.
h3 - Choosing Content
p - Videos generally will not be accessible. Thus, they have to be paired with an accessible transcript and/or closed captions so that students will have an appropriate alternative. Automated captions frequently contain errors and may be more difficult to understand for many students, at least ensure that the captioning is correct and will not cause difficulties for those who require them. When deciding on what content to provide, try to ensure that it is appropriately accessible. Here is a list of some things to focus on when providing accessible content:
p - Closed captions
p - Captions preferably not automatically generated and do not contain errors
p - An accessible transcript
p - The video player is also accessible and usable for users
p - For more help request accessibility assistance for your content or schedule a training with a specialist, in person or online. These trainings can be as quick as 15mins or as long as an hour. They will teach you more about creating accessible content and answer additional questions you may have.
