title - Video Conferencing
h2 - UNDERSTAND
p - Learn more about the content format and common accessibility issues before working with video conferencing.
p - Video conferencing tools have become more used through the years. They make it easier to collaborate and communicate in real time. We will focus on Zoom and Microsoft Teams, but many of the principles discussed here apply to other video conferencing platforms such as Google Meet, Cisco WebEx, Skype, and so on.
h3 - FREQUENTLY ASKED QUESTIONS
h4 - When is video conferencing the best format to use?
p - Appropriate use cases include meetings with users in different geographical locations.
h4 - What are the benefits of video conferencing?
p - On zoom, live transcription can be assigned to provide real-time captioning of the meeting
p - Screen reader and assistive technology compatible
p - User customizations (font size, keyboard shortcuts, etc.)
p - Auto-generated captions
p - Teams has noise suppression to limit background noise
h4 - What are the limitations of video conferencing?
p - Auto-generated captions are helpful but not sufficient to support all deaf and hard of hearing users
p - High bandwidth required for optimal performance
p - Limited customization of caption style and placement
p - Features are different on different devices and versions of the software.
p - Limitations on mobile devices
p - Hosts enable accessibility features
h3 - RECOMMENDED SOFTWARE
h4 - Zoom
p - A video conferencing platform known for its ease of use and high-quality audio and video. It supports a wide range of features, including screen sharing, chat, and breakout rooms, making it a popular choice for large meetings, webinars, and virtual classrooms.
h4 - Microsoft Teams
p - A collaboration platform that integrates video conferencing with chat, file storage, and app integration. It's part of the Microsoft 365 suite, designed to serve as a central hub for teamwork and communication within a business or educational setting.
h2 - CREATE
p - Learn more about video call principles. Applying the Aspects will address the most common accessibility issues and make the call more accessible and user-friendly. Focus on the Best Practices after all the Aspects have been applied. They are “nice-to-haves” in accessibility but not as urgent.
h3 - APPLY THE ASPECTS
h4 - USABILITY
p - Offer multiple methods to join (computer, phone, mobile, etc.)
p - Share accessible versions of displayed materials in advance
p - Are participants given an opportunity to share accessibility needs ahead of time?
p - Is the chosen platform compatible with a wide variety of assistive technology?
h4 - REAL TEXT
p - Post-meeting edited transcript and notes are provided to attendees
p - Provide interactive links, files, and announcements in the chat
p - Are fonts consistent, legible, and accessible to all audiences?
h4 - STRUCTURE
p - Prepare materials and plan flow in advance for smooth transitions
p - Are visual structure and relationships clear from spoken content?
p - Is the progression of information and agendas logical?
h4 - SENSORY CHARACTERISTICS
p - Highlight active speakers for easier navigation
p - Convey all information independent of color
p - Are non-speaking participants muted to reduce background noise?
p - Does speaker overlap minimized to ensure clear communication?
p - Are color choices complementary, of sufficient contrast, and easy to distinguish?
h4 - VISUAL CONTENT
p - Avoid flashing or rapidly changing content
p - Presenter video quality ensures their face is clear and easily visible.
p - Are visuals designed to maintain clarify across different devices and screen sizes?
p - Is the integration of shared visual aids seamless and effective?
h3 - BEST PRACTICES
h4 - PLATFORM
p - Is the platform accessible?
p - Does the platform work with a variety of assistive technology and various input methods?
p - Does the platform support closed captioning and sign language interpreters (always visible) appropriately?
p - Does the platform support a computer-based, mobile-based, and phone call-based audience?
h4 - PRESENTATION
p - Is there an assigned facilitator to lead the discussion and agenda?
p - Are participants encouraged to show a clear video of their face when speaking?
p - Is audio and video clear from all presenters and facilitators?
p - Is speaker overlap minimized?
p - Are non-speaking participants muted to minimize background noise?
h4 - TECHNICAL
p - Are connections, shared media, and backups tested in advance?
p - Are displayed and reference materials provided in advance to participants?
p - Do external, embedded, and referenced resources meet accessibility requirements of the format?
p - Are notes or recordings shared between participants for later reference and review?
h2 - EVALUATE
p - Walk through a quick accessibility check for content that is already been created to evaluate its accessibility. For an in-depth evaluation download the content checklist to get a quantitative score.
h2 - DECIDE
p - Learn more about what to do with evaluation data and how to pick which content is most accessible.
h3 - Remediation
p - After evaluating your content, you may find several accessibility issues. Prioritize remediating content that has the greatest impact on the user.
p - Once you've decided on the most critical accessibility issues to address, it's time to implement changes. This may involve:
p - Captions and Transcripts: Provide accurate captions for all video content and a full transcript for all audio.
p - Keyboard Navigation: Ensure all controls, such as mute and video on/off, are fully operable using only a keyboard.
p - Screen Reader Compatibility: All on-screen elements, including participant names and chat messages, must be correctly labeled for screen readers.
p - Chat and Recordings: Ensure the chat feature is accessible with good color contrast and that all recorded content is also made accessible.
p - For more help request accessibility assistance for your content or schedule a training with a specialist, in person or online. These trainings can be as quick as 15mins or as long as an hour. They will teach you more about creating accessible content and answer additional questions you may have.


