title - Visual Content
h2 - The Principle
p - Just like sensory characteristics, visual content needs to be paired with a computer-understandable alternative. These alternatives include features like:
p - alternative text (concise description)
p - long descriptions (detailed description)
p - audio descriptions (separate audio track describing visuals)
p - verbal descriptions (descriptions of visuals in main audio)
p - descriptive transcripts (audio and visuals as text)
p - Visual content includes a wide range of content, including images, graphics, charts, diagrams, maps, icons, emojis, videos, and animations. These elements can make content easier to understand. However, their meaning and interpretation is often influenced and shaped by the context, purpose, and audience perspective.
h2 - Image Best Practices
p - Images play a valuable role in digital content. They provide a second view of information. However, they can also present unique accessibility concerns and challenges. We will review key points and best practices for digital accessibility with including images in your content.
p - These principles can be applied to other visual content as well.
p - Informative vs Decorative - decorative images are present for decorative purposes only and do not add any informational value to the content. Informative images convey information to the user and require alternative text to convey that informational value to technology.
p - Alternative Text - alternative text (or alt text for short) is a brief visual description of an image. Every informative image is required to have alt text. Alt text should be the most basic version of what the visual shows and is limited to a sentence or two (approximately 250 characters or less).
p - Long Description - long descriptions are detailed descriptions of an image when it cannot adequately be contained in alt text. There are no limits on how long a long description can be. Instead of including a long description, consider adding the information in the surrounding text.
h2 - Video Best Practices
p - Visuals - informational visuals in a video need to have sufficient contrast (4.5:1 ratio). It is helpful to describe any visuals on screen as part of the script.
p - Chapters - chapters can be used to break the video into sections and provide easy navigation to specific points of the video.
p - Captions - a complete transcription of the soundtrack or audio track of the video should be recorded in the captions. This will include all relevant and informational sounds and dialogue.
p - Audio Description - audio description provides information about actions, characters, scene changes, on-screen text, and other visual content not able to be understood from the main audio track or soundtrack. If the audio provides adequate description of visuals, there may not be a need for an audio description. This may be provided in a format accessible to a screen reader, as a separate video, as a separate audio track file, or other options.
p - Descriptive Transcript - descriptive transcripts are a direct alternative of the video. They are not generally used alongside or with the video but are independently able to provide the same information and an equivalent experience as the video. Descriptive transcripts need to follow all rules for accessibility of their format. An example is the written transcripts for general conference talks along with the videos on the church's website.
h2 - Moving Images
p - Moving images and animations make content more engaging and fun to use. However, these will require additional considerations for digital accessibility. Moving images or animations may cause discomfort or health issues for some users. When thoughtfully implemented, moving images and animations can enhance understanding and engagement without causing distraction, discomfort, or distress.
p - Some examples include: GIFs, transitions, loading animations, UI animations, 3D models, scroll animations, simulations, and automatic carousels.
p - Controls - provide an option to reduce motion such as a stop button or speed adjustments.
p - Alternatives - add a caption or description just like you would with an image or video. It's also possible to provide a static alternative that doesn't move. Avoid using animations as the only way of sharing critical information
p - Flashing - avoid flashing or rapidly changing content (more than 3 flashes per second), provide a warning beforehand if this is the case.


---End of Page---
