h2 - Tips for Writing Alternative Text
h2 - Logos
p - Logo alt text should contain the name of the company, organization, or product. It should specify it is a logo and include any additional text in the logo.
p - To determine if your image is a logo or functions as a logo:
p - Does the image represent the identity of an organization, brand, or product?
p - Is the logo used to communicate ownership, affiliation, or authenticity?
p - Is the logonotfunctional (e.g., linking to a homepage)?
h2 - Functional
p - When an image serves a function (button, interactive element, link, etc.), the alt text should convey the function or action triggered. The alt text should follow the rules of the function and no longer be descriptive of the visual.
p - For example, an image of a printer with the alt text “Print this page”, or a logo that functions as a button with the alt text “BYU-Idaho home”.
p - To determine if your image is functional:
p - Does the image act as a link, button, or other interactive element?
p - Would any information or function be lost if the image were removed?
h2 - Images of Text
p - Images of text should be avoided. We recommend using CSS to style real text instead of using an image of text.
h2 - Complex
p - For images that are too complex to provide a complete alternative in the alt text, you will need a two-part alternative. First is the alternative text, which should be a summary of the image. Second is the detailed description, which will provide the full visual information of the image.
p - To determine if your image is complex:
p - Does the image contain data, relationships, or trends that need explanation or structure?
p - Does the image require interpretation of color, labels, or other structure?
p - If I write an alternative with all of the visual information in the image, will it be longer than a sentence or two (250 characters approximately)?
h3 - Example
p - Alt Text: Bar graph titled Days of Snow
p - Description: The X axis shows the number of days of snow ranging from 0 to 16, and the Y axis shows the months of December, January, February, and March. Data: December, 2; January, 6; February, 14; March, 3.
h2 - Groups
p - Groups of images part of a sequence or collage generally convey one overall theme or piece of information. Add the semantic alternative to the first image in the group or sequence and mark the rest as decorative.
p - Example: “Two out of five stars”.
p - To determine if your images are a group:
p - Do the images collectively convey one message or theme?
p - Are the images used to show a sequence, comparison, or collection?
h2 - Maps
p - The alt text for a map should summarize the purpose. Is it to show geography, directions, statistical data, or a specific location?
p - If the map contains significant detail, include long description that includes important locations, routes, markers, or areas.
h2 - Emotional Content
p - If an image conveys emotion or sets a tone, describe the emotions or atmosphere. Images that convey humor and irony need to have a detailed description without adding interpretation or assumptions.
p - To determine emotion and tone of your image:
p - Do I have an emotional response to the image?
p - What visual elements contribute to the mood or tone of the image?
p - What is the underlying message or story conveyed by the image?
p - Would the absence of the image reduce the emotional impact of the content?
h3 - Example
p - Meme. Top text: Makes memes accessible with alt text. Central image: child with fist clenched in pumping motion. Bottom: Righteous.
