title - Website
h2 - Understand
p - Learn more about the content format and common digital accessibility issues before working with website content.
p - There are a lot of difference pieces that go into creating good accessible web content. Understanding these pieces and how they fit together is crucial. Each pieces contributes differently to the overall accessibility and using them in combination appropriately can make a significant impact on your content accessibility.
p - HTML should be the foundation of web content, using semantic HTML. ARIA should be used with caution to fill accessibility gaps, particularly with custom controls. CSS should enhance the visual presentation. JavaScript should be used to add interactive experiences and communicate dynamic changes.
h3 - Frequently Asked Questions
h4 - When is a website the best format?
p - Website are often the best format for accessibility when the content is dynamic, interactive, or needs to be updated frequently.
h4 - What are the benefits of websites?
p - Their inherent adaptability to different devices and screen sizes, the ability for users to customize display settings like font size and color, and the capacity for dynamic, interactive content.
h4 - What are the limitations of websites?
p - Typically requires more technical knowledge and expertise. It also require an internet connection to access.
h2 - Create
p - Learn more about website creation principles. Applying the Aspects will address the most common digital accessibility issues and make the content more accessible and user-friendly. Focus on the Best Practices after all the Aspects have been applied. They are “nice-to-haves” in accessibility but not as urgent.
h3 - Apply the Aspects
h4 - Usability
p - Website is responsive to user customization (screen size, magnification, high-contrast, auto-fill, etc.)
p - Communicate and associate error and status messages (semantically and visually)
p - Organization is consistent and predictable
p - Can repeated content be skipped?
p - Can all content be accessed and interacted with various input types without traps?
p - Is focus predictable, visible, and logical?
h4 - Real Text
p - Make text selectable and accurate
p - Is thelangattribute defined in the<html>tag and when necessary?
p - Is text information selectable and accurate, not an image of text?
p - Are semantic elements used wherever possible?
h4 - Structure
p - Page title is descriptive and unique
p - Each element style is unique from other elements (visually and semantically)
p - One, and always one,<H1>element per page
p - Are structural elements (headings, tables, links, lists, buttons, etc.) used appropriately?
p - Are adjacent links grouped as a single link?
p - Do tables include a caption and header cells with appropriate scope and span?
h4 - Sensory Characteristics
p - Convey all information independent of color
p - Dynamically size and space elements for customization
p - Are informational sensory characteristics paired with a semantic partner?
p - Is color contrast sufficient between text or user interface and background?
h4 - Visual Content
p - All images have an alt attribute
p - Descriptive images have a blank alt attribute
p - Do all meaningful visuals (videos, images, diagrams, etc.) have an appropriate semantic alternative (alt text, long description, descriptive transcript, etc.)?
p - Do functional visuals have a semantic alternative that conveys their function?
h3 - Best Practices
h4 - Design
p - Is design and layout consistent across pages?
p - Are sizing, spacing, and layout techniques used help with content flow and interactions?
p - Are interactive elements distinct from static content?
p - Does content flow and build naturally and logically?
h4 - Technical
p - Do external and embedded resources meet accessibility requirements of the format?
p - Has content been reviewed and/or created with the aspects in mind?
p - Has accessibility been tested using automated and/or manual methods and all found issues resolved?
p - Is navigation and help easy to find and use?
p - Can users report accessibility barriers or issues?
h2 - Evaluate
p - Walk through a quick accessibility check for content that is already been created to evaluate its digital accessibility. For an in-depth evaluation download the content checklist to get a quantitative score.
h3 - Quick Accessibility Check
p - Run an automated checker - Use automated tools to check for code-based accessibility problems. If there are any errors or alerts, this gives you a good idea of where to start fixing digital accessibility.
p - Review heading hierarchy - Use a tool to show you the page structure and/or heading outline. Look for empty headings, skipped levels, and organization that doesn't make sense.
p - Check focus - Use the Tab key to move through interactive elements. Pay attention to the order of elements, the visual indication of where it is, and that all elements are focused.
h2 - Decide
p - Learn more about what to do with evaluation data and how to pick which content is most accessible.
h3 - Selecting Accessible Content
p - Determining accessible web content can be more difficult. When deciding on what content to provide, try to ensure that it is appropriately accessible. Sites that are widely known and reputable will be more likely to contain accessible features. Sites that contain clear headings and have less visual effects are also more likely to be more accessible. Here is a list of some things to focus on when providing accessible content:
p - Uses proper headings and semantic HTML
p - Is easily navigable without repetition
p - Alt text for images
p - Sufficient color contrast for text and images
p - Follows established website conventions (i.e. navbar, footer, title)
p - For more help request accessibility assistance for your content or schedule a training with a specialist, in person or online. These trainings can be as quick as 15mins or as long as an hour. They will teach you more about creating accessible content and answer additional questions you may have.
