title - When to Use: Microsoft Word, HTML, or PDF?
p - Creating accessible content ensures that all audiences can fully engage with your materials. This guide will help you understand the accessibility benefits and limitations of three common content formats: Word, HTML, and PDF. Use this information to help you determine when it is appropriate to use each method for your needs.
p - We recommend using HTML webpages whenever possible, as they are generally the most accessible and adaptive. PDFs should only be used as a last resort when content is intended for print.
h2 - HTML
p - HTML is a highly compatible and responsive language, and when used with best practices, it's easy to update and instantly available to users on any device. While some knowledge of its structure is required, it's a flexible and adaptable tool for creating accessible, mobile-friendly web pages.
p - Best Uses - HTML is ideal for creating mobile-friendly web pages and for content that needs frequent updates.
p - Benefits - HTML is highly flexible and adaptable, supporting all accessibility standards. Using semantic HTML helps screen readers, and it's easy to adjust for readability and contrast. Simple and complex tables can also be made accessible with semantic elements.
p - Limitations - HTML may require additional support for advanced multimedia. Additionally, accessibility can be a challenge with nested structures or merged cells.
h2 - Microsoft Word
p - Microsoft Word is an easy-to-use and widely compatible tool for creating and distributing documents on both desktops and mobile devices. However, if documents aren't created with accessibility in mind from the start, remediation can be a tedious process.
p - Best Uses - Word is best used for creating drafts, text documents, and templates.
p - Benefits - It has an easy-to-use built-in accessibility checker. Documents can be structured with headings, lists, and tables, and the native tools allow for accessible, simple tables with clear headers, rows, and columns.
p - Limitations - Word is limited to its native accessibility features. Complex tables cannot be made fully accessible due to these limitations.
h2 - PDF
p - PDFs are difficult to edit for accessibility and lack responsive features, though they are compatible with most devices. Ensuring full accessibility is a complex process. They must be tagged correctly, as auto-generated tags are usually insufficient, and manual tagging is a long and laborious process.
p - Best Uses - PDFs are best used for creating printable final versions and downloadable forms.
p - Benefits - A key benefit of PDFs is that they retain a fixed layout for printed versions. The format isn't limited to its original formatting, as you can customize tags and reading order. If tagged correctly, a PDF can also support both simple and complex tables.
p - Limitations - PDFs are complex to make accessible due to their tagging requirements. They also lack responsive and interactive features. Furthermore, auto-tagged content is insufficient, and manually remediating tags is a lengthy process.


---End of Page---
---Beginning of Page---

title - Word Processing
h2 - Understand
p - Learn more about the content format and common digital accessibility issues before working with word processing documents.
p - Word processing documents are the most widely known and used form of digital content. Word processing documents are primarily text-based content, presented in a linear fashion. A few examples of word processing software (that produce word processing documents) are Google Docs, Microsoft Word, Pages, WordPerfect, and LibreOffice.
h3 - Frequently Asked Questions
h4 - When are word documents the best format choice?
p - A few key times when a word processing document might be the best option:
p - Regular editing and updating
p - Collaborative drafting, editing, or group content creation
p - Drafts or temporary versions
p - Internal business documents (familiar format)
p - Simple, text-based content
h4 - What are the benefits of Word documents?
p - Easy to make accessible, update, or change
p - User customization
p - Easy to skim, navigate, and digest
p - More future-proof with advances and changes in technology or operating systems
h4 - What are the limitations of Word documents?
p - Limited to the semantic options available in the word processing document
p - Limited control over complex content (tables, multi-column layouts, mixed media)
p - Non-linear content structure options are limited
p - Potentially requires a specific software to view or use the document
p - Lack of accessible support for forms
h3 - Recommended Software
h4 - Microsoft Word
p - This word processor allows users to create accessible documents by using built-in heading styles, creating alternative text for images and tables, and ensuring proper reading order. It also includes an Accessibility Checker to identify and fix common issues, which helps users meet accessibility standards.
h4 - Google Docs
p - Known for its real-time collaboration, Google Docs also provides accessibility features. It supports screen reader compatibility and keyboard navigation, and allows users to add alt text to images. The web-based nature and compatibility with assistive technologies make it accessible for many users.
h4 - LibreOffice
p - As a free, open-source word processor, LibreOffice Writer is a powerful tool for creating accessible documents. It offers features for tagging content, adding alt text to images, and exporting documents to accessible formats like tagged PDF, helping to ensure that content is readable by assistive technologies.
h2 - Create
p - Learn more about word processing document creation principles. Applying the Aspects will address the most common digital accessibility issues and make the content more accessible and user-friendly. Focus on the Best Practices after all the Aspects have been applied. They are “nice-to-haves” in accessibility but not as urgent.
h3 - Apply the Aspects
h4 - Usability
p - Repeat all important information from the header and footer.
p - Make all content part of the linear flow.
p - Verify headings in navigation pane (no blanks, skipped levels, etc.)
p - The user should be able to access all the content using only the arrow keys.
p - All content should receive focus on a logical order.
h4 - Real Text
p - Set the document language
p - Avoid text boxes, WordArt, SmartArt, and Drop Caps.
p - Insert Math and STEM content semantically.
p - Set the language for the document. If any other language is used in the document it should be set for that section of text.
p - Text should be selectable and accurate, not an image of text.
h4 - Structure
p - Use styles to apply formatting and structure consistently.
p - Give links descriptive visible text and a ScreenTip (when applicable).
p - Add appropriate structure through built-in tools and design.
p - Show structure visually as well as semantically.
p - The document should be free of all text boxes and other non-linear important content.
h4 - Sensory Characteristics
p - Convey all information independent of color.
p - Keep structure, flow, and design simple.
p - Use layout options to add white space.
p - Use paragraph layout and spacing options instead of multiple blank characters.
p - Color contrast should be sufficient between foreground and background for all informational content.
h4 - Visual Content
p - Anchor objects to the linear content.
p - Use built-in tools for stylistic design (borders, indentations, margins, sections, columns, etc.)
p - Informational images have alt text; decorative images are ignored.
p - The semantic alternative should be adjusted to not repeat context.
p - If there is a need for long description, it should be included either in the context or linked near the visual.
h3 - Best Practices
h4 - Content
p - Ensure that all informational content is in the linear flow of text, the language clear, simple, and direct, the content is organized in a logical and predictable manner, and all jargon, technical terms, and acronyms are defined or explained. The fonts, layout, and formatting should be consistent throughout the whole document.
h4 - Technical
p - Ensure that external and embedded resources meet accessibility requirements and that the file has a descriptive title.
h2 - Evaluate
p - Walk through a quick accessibility check for content that is already been created to evaluate its digital accessibility. For an in-depth evaluation download the content checklist to get a quantitative score.
h3 - Quick Accessibility Check
p - Run an automated checker - Use an automated to review color and contrast, media and illustrations, tables, structure, and access. If there are any issues, this gives you a good idea of where to start fixing for accessibility.
p - Review navigation pane - Turn on the outline viewer (navigation pane) to see anything that is marked with an outline level (headings). Look for blank lines, skipped levels (indented too far), and organization that doesn't make sense.
p - Show paragraph marks - Show paragraph marks or non-printing characters to see the structure of the document. Scroll through the document and look for 2 or more consecutive blank characters (spaces, tabs, paragraphs). Pay attention to page breaks and end of documents.
h2 - Decide
p - Learn more about what to do with evaluation data and how to pick which content is most accessible.
h3 - Finding Content
p - Word Processing Documents are easier when it comes to accessibility. Editors generally offer accessibility checkers and things such as headings can be easily seen in the table of contents are just by examining the text. When deciding on what content to provide, try to ensure that it is appropriately accessible. Here is a list of some things to focus on when providing accessible content:
p - Proper use of headings
p - Alt text
p - Table of contents
p - High contrast between text and background
p - For more help request accessibility assistance for your content or schedule a training with a specialist, in person or online. These trainings can be as quick as 15mins or as long as an hour. They will teach you more about creating accessible content and answer additional questions you may have.
